<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Qinghua University to Launch Small Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- China's prestigious Qinghua
University, one of the several top institutions of higher
education in the country, will launch a small satellite before the
end of next year, university President Wang Dazhong announced here
today.
</P>
<P>
The satellite, known as "Qinghua I", weighs about 75 kg and
measures 1.2 meters in height, Wang disclosed at a meeting to mark
the inauguration of the university's Space Flight Research
Center.
</P>
<P>
He said that it will be used in fields such as space research,
remote control, environmental and disaster surveillance, special
civilian telecommunications and education in popular science.
</P>
<P>
The research and development of the satellite will be jointly
conducted by Qinghua University and a British University.
</P>
<P>
"Our research and development of small satellites heralds our
entry into the the field of space navigation," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the new study field will help promote development
in the disciplines of electronics, precision instruments,
mechanics, computer science, and automation, and thereby
contribute to the advance of the national economy and that of
science and research in national defence.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
