<HEADLINE> Pakistan Not to Sign CTBT Till Lifting of Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The joint sitting of the
Parliament completed debate on the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty
(CTBT) Wednesday with a pledge not to become a signatory, till all
sanctions against Pakistan are lifted.
</P>
<P>
The four-day debate, first of its kind to seek opinion of the
parliamentarians on the issue of national importance by both the
houses, remained controversial for the opposition.
</P>
<P>
In his winding up speech, Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz claimed
that his country would sign the treaty only if all sanctions
against it are lifted. He reiterated that the government will not
compromise on national integrity and sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said that becoming a signatory to CTBT will not take away
Pakistan's nuclear deterrence and its capability.
</P>
<P>
However, he also said that in case India goes for further
nuclear test Pakistan too can withdraw from the treaty and go for
more tests.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan acquired its nuclear capability with great effort and
determination and no country of the world can now take it back,"
the foreign minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
