<HEADLINE> Pakistani FM to Visit Iran Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Sartaj Aziz will make a visit to Iran Thursday to promote
conciliation and avert the dangers inherent in an escalation
between Iran and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
A press release by the Foreign Ministry Wednesday said that
"Pakistan is deeply concerned over the heightening of tension
between Iran and Afghanistan" which could pose a serious threat to
the peace and security of the entire region.
</P>
<P>
Aziz will be carrying a letter from Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
for Iranian president Mohammad Khatami. He will reassure the
Iranian leadership of Pakistan's commitment to the abiding
friendship between Pakistan and Iran which transcends all
vicissitudes, according to the press release.
</P>
<P>
It said that the foreign minister will also emphasize the
allegation of Pakistan's interference in Afghanistan was "a
fabrication of the enemies of Pakistan-Iran friendship."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has been in constant touch with the afghan leadership
as a part of its peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
The press release noted the several visits by Pakistan's
delegations to Kandahar which resulted in the release and
repatriation of five Iranian prisoners, and the efforts by
Pakistan which led to the location and transport to Iran of seven
dead bodies of the 11 Iranian personnel in the northern afghan
town of Mazar-i-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan hoped that Iran and Afghanistan will resolve their
difference through peaceful negotiations, and will continue to
cooperate closely with the two countries to defuse the present
crisis, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has also urged the United Nations to play its role in
averting a potential conflict and helping the cause of peace and
security in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
