<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon, Armenia Signs Cooperation Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon and Armenia Wednesday
signed four cooperation agreements concerning tourism, high
education and preventing dual taxation, the Lebanese National News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Armenian Prime Minister Armen Darbinyan and his
Lebanese counterpart Rafik Hariri attended the signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Hariri said at a news conference later that commercial exchange
between the two countries is limited and hoped bilateral ties will
be boosted through the agreements signed and to be signed in the
near future and visits by two countries' businessmen.
</P>
<P>
He paid tribute to the positive role played by Lebanese of
Armenian origin in constructing Lebanon, a country which is
recovering from a 1975-1990 civil war.
</P>
<P>
"I hope they can make more efforts for promoting ties between
Lebanon and Armenia," Hariri said.
</P>
<P>
Some 110,000 Armenian emigrants are living in Lebanon, and
18 percent of Lebanese industrial enterprises are owned by
them.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Darbinyan expressed hope that the two
countries further develop their relations, especially in the
economic sector, adding the agreements signed with Lebanon will
pave the way for that purpose.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics from Lebanon's economy ministry, trade
between Lebanon and Armenia stood at about 1 million U.S. dollars
each year.
</P>
<P>
The Armenian premier came to Lebanon Wednesday morning for
a three-day official visit.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, he will also meet with Lebanese President
Elias Hrawi and House Speaker Nabih Berry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
