<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Leader to Visit UK, U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Head of State,
General Abdulsalami Abubakar will visit Britain later this month,
where he will leave for New York of the U.S., the official News
Agency of Nigeria (NAN) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A source at the presidency in Abuja, however, told Xinhua that
the visit can not be confirmed until next Monday.
</P>
<P>
NAN quoted diplomatic sources in London as saying that
Abubakar will arrive in London on September 22 and go to New York
the following day.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar will meet with the British Prime Minister Tony Blair
and other government officials during his stay in London, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton said recently that he is
interested in meeting with Abubakar during the general's visit to
the New York to attend the 53rd session of the United Nations
General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian military officials have been banned from visits to
both Britain and the United States, as part of the sanctions
imposed on Nigeria since 1995, when the then military government
of late General Sani Abacha hanged author Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight
other minority activists on murder charges.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's relations with the West have improved since Abubakar
took office in June after the death of Abacha. The new leader's
liberal policy and commitment to democratization has won him the
understanding and support of world leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
