<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. to Send Relief Mission to Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
agreed to send an assessment mission to Afghanistan on condition
that the Taliban guarantee safety of the U.N. personnel in the
Asian country, and the condition was accepted by Taliban, U.N.
spokesman Fred Eckhard said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Taliban, which does not hold Afghanistan's United Nations seat
even though it controls most of the country, also asked the United
Nations to mediate to defuse tensions with Iran over the recent
killings of Iranian diplomats in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"The United Nations has agreed, on an exceptional basis, to
send an assessment mission to Bamiyan," which fell to Taliban on
Sunday, he said, adding that "this is conditional on the Taliban
authorities guaranteeing the safety of U.N. personnel."
</P>
<P>
The conditional agreement was reached following a Tuesday
meeting in New York between senior U.N. officials and Taliban
representatives.
</P>
<P>
Sergio Vieira de Mello, under-secretary-general for
humanitarian affairs, and Kieran Prendergast,
under-secretary-general for political affairs, met with Taliban
representatives to discuss a number of important issues.
</P>
<P>
The conditions cover direct flights by U.N. planes into and
out of Bamiyan, the escorts by Taliban for the U.N. mission
during its duration in Afghanistan, security constraints to
prevent U.N. personnel from staying overnight, the free
utilization of U.N. communication equipment and the mission's
unfettered access to all affected populations in the Bamiyan
area, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the senior U.N. officials made it clear
to the Taliban representatives that the proposed mission "is
being undertaken on an exceptional basis and does not imply a
full scale return of United Nations international staff to
Afghanistan, he said.
</P>
<P>
"For this to occur certain conditions have to be met," he
said, referring to earlier U.N. decision to withdraw its workers
from Afghanistan for security concerns.
</P>
<P>
"This morning, the Taliban representative in New York informed
the U.N. that he had got agreement from his authorities in
Kandahar, Afghanistan, to all these points," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The secretary-general will undertake further high-level
consultations in the margins of the General Assembly meeting next
week," the spokesman, adding that "the secretary-general is also
currently considering other measures to help reduce tension in the
region."
</P>
<P>
The Security Council on Tuesday condemned the killing of the
Iranian diplomats and said the act had seriously increased
tension in the region.
</P>
<P>
Iran has maintained a buildup of some 70,000 troops and a lot
of military equipment in its borders with Afghanistan while
Iranian leaders said that Iran would use whatever means they saw
fit to respond to the killing of Iranian diplomats in Afghanistan
following the Taliban captured Mazar-i-Sharif. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Recommends to Extend Mandate of UN Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Wednesday recommended that the Security Council
extend the mandate of the United Nations Mission for the
Referendum in Western Sahara (MINURSO) through the end of October
to allow time for negotiations on the issues of "contested
tribes."
</P>
<P>
In his latest report to the Security Council, Annan welcomed
the completion of the identification of 147,000 applicants for
participation in the referendum, which will allow the people of
Western Sahara to choose between independence or integration
with Morocco.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General expressed concern that the question of
the identification of applicants from three "contested groups"
remains outstanding.
</P>
<P>
The issue will be dealt with in talks brokered by the
Secretary-General's Personal Envoy James Baker III which are
expected to begin by late September or early October.
</P>
<P>
"My personal envoy is pursuing his contacts with the parties
so that he may assess whether the Settlement Plan can be carried
out in its present form or whether there may be adjustments to
it, acceptable to the parties, that would improve the chances of
implementing it," the U.N. chief said in the report.
</P>
<P>
"If he concludes that, even with such adjustments, the Plan
cannot be carried out, he would advise me on other courses of
action that could be pursued," he added.
</P>
<P>
 Western Sahara was a Spanish colony until 1976 when Spain
withdrew and released itself from international responsibility
over the territory, which was subsequently occupied by Morocco,
a move opposed by the Popular Front for the Liberation of Saguia
el-Hamra and Rio de Oro POLISARIO Front. The POLISARIO took up
arms against Moroccan forces.
</P>
<P>
Following diplomatic initiatives by the Organization of African
Unity and the United Nations, the Security Council approved a
settlement plan for Western Sahara in 1990, under which there
would be a ceasefire, and a transitional period during which the
Special representative of the Secretary-General would be in charge
of all matters relating to the referendum, assisted by MINURSO.
</P>
<P>
 The plan was eventually bogged down by the two parties's
differences on certain groups of people to be included in the
referendum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
