<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda's Involvement in Congo (K) Involuntary: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni has said that his country's involvement in the crisis in
the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) is involuntary.
</P>
<P>
This is forced on Uganda, the president said while addressing
Parliament about this issue Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Kampala's involvement in Congo, indirectly last year and a bit
more directly this year, is mainly because of the threats to
Uganda's security that emanate from there in the form of National
Army for the Liberation of Uganda in the past and more recently,
Allied Democratic Forces, Museveni said.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's two involvements in Congo in recent times started
with its involvement in Rwanda, he pointed out, explaining that
this involvement is only to prevent genocide.
</P>
<P>
"We are in Congo primarily for our security. We have not yet
taken part, in any serious way, in the fighting that has been
going on there. If we were to do so in future, it would be
because the region has failed to solve the problem, especially,
the problem of our security," he said.
</P>
<P>
On this occasion, he also expressed his opposition to
invitation for foreign involvement, arguing that foreign
involvement in Congo is due to the internal weaknesses of the
Congolese leaders.
</P>
<P>
During the time of National Resistance Movement, we have faced
a lot of problems, both internal and with our neighbors, but we
never call on neighbors or distant friends to help us with
troops, he asserted.
</P>
<P>
To ask foreigners to defend one is to promulgate a motion of
no confidence in oneself, Museveni said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
