<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Says More Ethiopians Expelled From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Office of Ethiopian
Government Spokeswoman Selome Taddesse said Wednesday that
Ethiopians are still suffering great hardship in Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued in Addis Ababa, the office said more
Ethiopians are being tortured, abused and expelled from Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
The office quoted 27-year-old Desta Atsbaha, one of the
deportees who worked as a driver, as saying that he had been
beaten at a police station and his 8,000 Nakfa (about 1,100 US
Dollars) in a bank had been confiscated.
</P>
<P>
Over 15,000 Ethiopians have been expelled from Eritrea since a
border dispute between the two countries erupted last May,
according to local reports.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea said earlier up to 17,000 of its nationals had been
expelled from Ethiopia since the border dispute. However,
Ethiopia said those deported for security reasons were only
around 4,000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
