<HEADLINE> Museveni: Security in Uganda Improved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni told Parliamentarians Wednesday afternoon that security
in the country has been improved.
</P>
<P>
In a speech which briefed the MPs on the crisis of the
Democratic Republic of Congo, Museveni said insecurity is
diminishing as the capacity of the state grows.
</P>
<P>
"Ugandans should be grateful to the National Resistance
Movement for building a powerful and cohesive national army which
is the base of all the growing security. It is a remarkable
achievement bearing in mind the starting point following the
collapse of the old Ugandan army," the president said.
</P>
<P>
The rebels in the north cannot establish a zone of control as
the Sudan People's Liberation Army has done in Sudan or the
Congolese rebels are doing in eastern Congo. This demonstrates
the capacity of the Uganda People's Defense Forces (UPDF).
</P>
<P>
That is why the rebels resort to terrorist attacks on
defenseless civilians rather than bon the barracks of the UPDF, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The security task now is to stop these cowardly attacks on
civilians, he said, arguing that to compromise with terrorism is
to invite more of it.
</P>
<P>
With the support of MPs for the army and security in general,
he said he is confident that terrorism will eventually be
eliminated from his country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
