<HEADLINE> Jordanian Crown Prince Calls for Progress in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan,
the Regent, Wednesday urged the United States` Middle East peace
envoy Dennis Ross to reactivate the long-stalled
Palestinian-Israeli peace process.
</P>
<P>
Hassan called for collective efforts by all the concerned
parties to overcome the obstacles facing implementation of the
U.S. proposal, which asks Israel to further evacuate from 13.1
percent of the occupied West Bank in order to enliven the peace
process that has been deadlocked since last March.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after his meeting with Hassan and Prime
Minister Fayez Tarawneh, Ross said that the meeting was fruitful,
adding that "We really try to change the atmosphere in the
region, especially when it comes to making peace."
</P>
<P>
Ross in his statement admitted that he achieved some progress
with the Palestinians and Israel over the implementation of the
U.S. proposal, but "there remain differences and we have to find
ways to overcome those differences."
</P>
<P>
He added that he will stay in the region for a couple of days
for this aim.
</P>
<P>
Ross arrived here earlier Wednesday to brief Hassan on the
results of his current visit to the region.
</P>
<P>
Ross arrived in the region last Wednesday in a new effort to
break the differences between Israel and the Palestinians on a
host of issues contained in the U.S. proposal. He met Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat respectively during the past days.
</P>
<P>
However, both Palestinian and Israeli government officials have
 said that Ross failed to realize his aim of the current mission
which has been his first since May.
</P>
<P>
Jordan supports the Palestinians to establish an independent
state with its capital in Jerusalem, but it also sticks to a
policy of normalizing ties with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has been the second and last Arab country that signed peace
treaty with Israel. The first one is Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
