<HEADLINE> U.N. Special Envoy Solicits Support for Angolan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- United Nations special envoy
to Angola Issa Diallo made an appeal Wednesday to diplomatic
missions of various countries in Angola, hoping that they will
continue their effort in helping the country realize a lasting
peace.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Diallo briefed reporters on
what he had done since he assumed his post on August 28 this
year. He has made contacts and consultations mainly with the
diplomatic missions concerning the current peace process
situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
The current situation in Angola is "very difficult", he
admitted, adding that since the Angolan government has severed
relations whth opposition leader President Jonas Savimbi of the
National Union for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) and
regards the breakaway group "the UNITA Renovation Committee" as
the only dialogist, the Peace Process United Commission meeting
is no longer able to be held, he said.
</P>
<P>
The special envoy pointed out that at a time when Angola peace
process has come to a deadlock and the relations between the two
warring sides are becoming increasingly strained, he can not but
ask the international community, the various diplomatic missions
in particular, to continue their effort and help remove the
obstacles on the road to peace process.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the resolution on Angola adopted by the United
Nations Tuesday which extends the term of office of the U.N.
observers group for an extra 30 days, Diallo held that so long as
the various sides who signed the Lusaka Peace Protocol show a
sufficient political will, the peace process can surely be
completed during this period.
</P>
<P>
However, Diallo still refused to give any comment on such
issues concerning the suspension of UNITA members in the
government and parliament and Angolan government's request for
the U.N. to recognize the breakaway "UNITA Renovation Committee".
</P>
<P>
The special envoy has over the past few days conducted
intensive secret talks with the diplomatic missions. He met
Tuesday with U.S. ambassador Donald Steinberg and Germany's
ambassador Hendrik Done who is also European Union representative
in Angola. Hendrik Done expressed European Union's pledge to give
Angola assistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
