<HEADLINE> Ugandan MP Urges Withdrawal of Troops From DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- A Ugandan member of
parliament has said that he will table a motion on September 17
to urge the government to withdraw its troops from the Democratic
Repubic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
After the conference at which President Yoweri Museveni
addressed the Parliament about the Congo issue Wednesday
afternoon, Hon. Aggren Awori, a MP from the Busia district, told
Xinhua that he will table the motion at the next session of the
legislature.
</P>
<P>
He listed three main reasons for the withdrawal of troops.
</P>
<P>
First, it is against international laws. Uganda's involvement
is not respect for other countries' integrity and sovereignty.
Second, Ugandan troops do not have wide support and lastly, if
the Allied Democratic Forces rebels attacked Ugandan districts,
Ugandan troops should be deployed on Ugandan territory, not on
the soil of DRC.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hon, Muyonga Samuel, a MP from the eastern district
of Mbale, said this motion will not be passed because it will not
win the support of the majority of MPs.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Awori tabled a motion calling for ceasefire and peace
talks between the rebels and Museveni. 
</P>
</TEXT>
