<HEADLINE> UN Envoy Says More Than Half of Displaced Persons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- U.N.
Secretary-General's Special Representative on the Situation of
Children in Armed Conflict said today that more than half of the
persons displaced by the conflict in Kosovo were children.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Olara Otunnu, who visited Kosovo
province of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia over the weekend,
described the plight of some 300,000 people who have been
displaced by military operations in the last several months. Of
these people, he said, approximately 50,000 were presently in
the open in the mountains and forests.
</P>
<P>
Otunnu said to avoid the present catastrophe from degenerating
into an even more dramatic tragedy, there should be at least a
ceasefire and a halt to hostilities. That, Otunnu said, could
allow the beginning of serious discussions about educational
institutions and how to return the displaced children to school.
</P>
<P>
He underlined the need for a significant international presence
on the ground to serve as a confidence building measure for people
to return to their homes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
