<HEADLINE> Syria Supports Ending Embargo on Libya, Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq
al-Sharaa Wednesday called for lifting the U.N. sanctions against
Libya and Iraq, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Sharaa, addressing the inaugural session of the Arab League
Foreign Ministerial Council here Wednesday, underlined the
necessity of ending the Libya-West crisis over the 1988 Lockerbie
crisis.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his country's backing of the resolutions adopted
by the Organization of African Unity (OAU), the Organization of
Islamic Conference (OIC) and the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) on
ending the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The OAU in its summit meeting in June adopted a resolution to
defy the sanctions starting from this month if the U.S. and
Britain fail to make compromise.
</P>
<P>
Sharaa voiced support for the Libyan requests for guarantees
that ensure a fair trial of the two Libyan suspects accused of
blowing up an American plane in 1988 over Lockerbie, Scotland,
which killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
Libya's failure to extradite them incurred the U.N. air, arms
and diplomatic embargo on the country in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Sharaa also called for lifting the international embargo imposed
against Iraq "according to a specific schedule." Meanwhile, he
urged Baghdad to comply with the relevant U.N. Security Council
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed sanctions against Iraq in 1990 after its
invasion of neighboring Kuwait, which can be removed only after
Iraq fully complies with U.N. resolutions and destroys its weapons
of mass destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
