<HEADLINE> Arafat Vows to Declare Palestinian State in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat Wednesday stressed his determination to
declare an independent Palestinian state in 1999 and called for a
new Arab summit to tackle the Mideast peace crisis.
</P>
<P>
In his address to the opening of the 110th Arab League Foreign
Ministerial Council meetings, Arafat appealed to Arab and Islamic
countries to buttress up the Palestinian aspiration for setting up
their own state with Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
"I firmly believe that the declaration of the Palestinian state
will get recognition and support from the Arab and Islamic world,"
Arafat told the Arab foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader has threatened to declare the
Palestinian state on May 4, 1999 when the deadline set by the 1993
Oslo agreement for final settlement expires.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said an Arab summit that involves all Arab leaders
should be convened to unify stances on the Arab-Israeli peace
process and confront various challenges and threats from the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks have languished for 18 months
over Israeli settlement building and long-delayed withdrawal from
the West Bank. U.S. mediation attempts have been frustrated by
Israel's rejection of a 13 percent redeployment plan.
</P>
<P>
Arafat blamed Israel for "playing tricks and stalling for time"
to avoid implementing its signed agreement with the Arab sides and
further redeployment from the occupied territories.
</P>
<P>
He also urged Washington to go public with the details of its
peace initiative to pressure Israel into fully accepting it.
</P>
<P>
Following his meeting with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
earlier Wednesday in Egypt's northern coastal city of Alexandria,
Arafat said the U.S. is still trying to extract an Israeli yes on
its initiative to break the Mideast peace stalemate.
</P>
<P>
"But it was still far for the U.S. to obtain this Israeli
approval despite that the Palestinians agreed on this initiative
six month ago," he lamented.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived in Alexandria Tuesday evening for a two-day
visit to Egypt for talks with Mubarak and to attend the Arab
League meeting in Cairo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
