<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bundesbank Upbeat about German Growth Despite Crises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The German central bank,
Bundesbank, said Wednesday that despite the financial crises in
Asia and Russia, Germany is still on course for solid growth
thanks to rising domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
In its September economic report, the Bundesbank noted that
risks faced by the German economy in foreign business had been
offset by positive development at home such as an increasing
willingness of companies to invest as well as rising private
consumption buoyed by an improving outlook for more jobs.
</P>
<P>
"The strengthened economic activities stand at the moment on a
broader basis compared with 1997 when Germany's growth was
supported first of all by the strongly increasing exports," the
Bundesbank report said.
</P>
<P>
The Bundesbank also did not see Germany's slowdown in the
second quarter as a negative signal for the economy, noting that
this had been largely expected given the extremely strong growth
in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
For the first half of 1998 as a whole, Germany's gross domestic
product (GDP) grew by 1.5 percent from the level of the second
half of last year, the central bank said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
