BONN, September 16 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel pledged Wednesday that the European Union would continue to
support Russia on its difficult path to democracy and market
economy despite its current crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We Europeans do not want a fair-weather partnership with
Russia. We want rather to continue and deepen the privileged
partnership between the EU and Russia also during difficult
times," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel's statement was made before a EU troika trip to Moscow
on Thursday to be made by foreign ministers of Britain, Austria
and Germany, which hold the previous, current and upcoming EU
presidency.
</P>
<P>
According to Kinkel, he and his Austrian and British
counterparts would focus their discussions with Russian leaders on
how the EU could help Russia in overcoming the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
While pledging continued support for Moscow, Kinkel also stress
that nobody could now spare the painful decisions that must be
made by Russia itself.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the Russian issue, the three EU foreign ministers
would also seek coordination with Russian leaders on the Kosovo
crisis, Kinkel said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
