<HEADLINE> Primakov Urges More Efforts to Defend Russian Interests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov on Wednesday urged his former colleagues in the Foreign
Ministry to continue defending Moscow's interests on the
international arena.
</P>
<P>
The 69-year-old former foreign minister listed a number of
priorities of Russian foreign policy, the Interfax news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The priorities include: helping the country to tackle its
internal problems, consistent defense of national interests
without sliding into confrontation, and the creation abroad of an
adequate image of the reforms implemented by the new government.
</P>
<P>
He said the main goal of Russia's foreign policy, particularly
now, is the creation of the most favorable conditions for Russia's
stable internal development.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said the Foreign Ministry
understood the tasks facing the diplomats and would do everything
possible to preserve and enlarge the potential built over the past
few years for cooperation with foreign countries and international
organizations.
</P>
<P>
"It's important to maintain high discipline and responsibility
at the ministry and to perform professional duties properly,"
Ivanov said. 
</P>
