<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Again Turns Heat on Belgrade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The NATO allies flexed their
muscles again on Wednesday by drafting a resolution to be put to
the United Nations for its mandate for intervention in the
crisis-ridden Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
A NATO official told the press that the draft resolution,
co-sponsored by France and Britain, would be introduced to the
U.N. Security Council within a few days.
</P>
<P>
The resolution will blame the violence by Serbian security
forces in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo and set certain demands
for Belgrade to meet, according to the official who asked to
remain unnamed.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the resolution, the official added, is to show that
there were limits to the patience of the international community
and that NATO stands ready to use military options if need be to
reinforce conditions for a political solution to the Kosovo
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The western military alliance has been studying a full range of
options in an effort to help solve the crisis that has reportedly
killed hundreds of people and left tens of thousands of people
living in makeshift shelters in Kosovo forests and mountains with
Winter fast approaching.
</P>
<P>
The NATO official said that Russia, that previously warned to
veto a U.N. resolution threatening the use of force in Kosovo,
showed its deep concern after its ambassador was briefed on
Wednesday on the status quo in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, French President Jacques Chirac told Russian
President Boris Yeltsin that he wanted the six-nation Contact
Group to meet on Kosovo next week with a new U.N. resolution.
</P>
<P>
Christopher Hill, United States peace envoy to Kosovo, also
briefed NATO ambassadors the same day on the ongoing intense
diplomatic efforts to find a peaceful solution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
