<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trial Re-Opens on Agusta/Dassault Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The trial of the
Agusta/Dassault corruption case, dubbed "trial of the century",
re-opened on Wednesday after a delay of eight days.
</P>
<P>
The Appeals Court of Belgium, the highest court in the country,
rejected all but two procedural demands put forward by the defense
that caused the delay after the trial went underway on September
2.
</P>
<P>
The court finally allowed separation of trials of two
defendants, Johan Delanghe and Serge Dassault.
</P>
<P>
The 10 other defendants, including former NATO
Secretary-General Willy Claes, will continue to sit in the dock of
the appeals court through the trial in a multi-billion franc
bribery case that also involved two other former Belgian cabinet
ministers.
</P>
<P>
Claes was forced to resign from the top NATO post in October
1995 when allegations rose that the Belgian foreign minister, who
had previously served as economy minister and was then responsible
for comparing rival bids among helicopter manufacturers, received
bribery.
</P>
<P>
The trial, that is expected to last well into December, will
investigate cash gifts allegedly given by the Italian company
Agusta and the French company Dassault in the late 1980s after
they won multi-billion franc contracts to supply Belgium with 46
A-106 helicopters and to refit the electronic systems in the
country's F-16 fighter jets.
</P>
<P>
The death of Socialist Party politician Andre Cools in 1991 led
to the discovery of irregularities in party funds that in turn led
to a report alleging that the granting of the 1988 contract to
Agusta was tainted with illegal acts and suggesting that technical
evaluations of the rival bids were handled by Belgian cabinet
members to make the Agusta bid more favorable.
</P>
<P>
The Agusta probe then led to allegations over Dassault
contract.
</P>
<P>
All the 12 accused, including ex-Belgian defense minister Guy
Coeme and former Socialist Party Chairman Guy Spitaels, have
denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
One key defendant, former Agusta President Raffaelo Teti, died
from a heart attack late last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Says "People Want Me to Go On" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton said Wednesday that Americans want to put the Lewinsky
matter behind them and want him to go on.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's joint news conference with visiting president of the
Czech Republic Vaclav Havel Wednesday was dominated by questions
about Clinton's relation with former White House intern Monic
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said Americans "want to put it behind them and they
want to go on -- and they want me to go on."
</P>
<P>
Asked whether he still had the moral authority to lead, the
president said firmly, "That is something you have to demonstrate
every day."
</P>
<P>
"I think that the right thing for our country and the right
thing for all people concerned is not to get mired in all the
details here but for me to focus on what I did, to acknowledge it,
to atone for it and then to work on my family, where I still have
a lot of work to do -- difficult work -- and to lead this
country," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said his legal defenses "should not obscure" the fact that
he is sorry for his acts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
