<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First U.S. Web-Only Bank Set to Launch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The first nationally
chartered bank in the United States to operate exclusively over
the World Wide Web is scheduled to go on line later this month or
early October, Computerworld reported on its online news
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
CompuBank, a Houston-based bank backed by 6 million U.S.
dollars in private funding, will offer several advantages over
existing Web-based banks or PC-based banking service. It will
charge no monthly fee and require no minimum balance for its basic
checking account, although a deposit of 200 U.S. dollars will be
required. Customers will be able to pay an unlimited number of
bills electronically for a flat fee of 5.5 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Web-only bank will also offer customers the ability to view
their statements and images of processed checks online. Customers
can also view their accounts from any browser that supports
128-bit encryption. There is no need for the proprietary PC
software many banks require online customers to use.
</P>
<P>
One downside is that, because of its small size, CompuBank owns
no automatic teller machines (ATM) of its own, forcing many
customers to pay fees if they use ATMs owned by other banks. But
the bank is looking for ATM networks that don't charge a fee to
outsiders and recommends its customers do withdrawals by using
their CompuBank ATM cards as debit cards at stores.
</P>
<P>
CompuBank also has to prove that its back-office systems can
handle hundreds, thousands or tens of thousands of customers,
Computerworld said. Currently, its Web site boasts only a static
billboard that says the service is "coming soon."
</P>
<P>
According to Computerworld, CompuBank has got approval to
operate as a bank in the country's all 50 states and the U.S.
territories from the U.S. Comptroller of the Currency in July. At
the same time, it qualified for coverage by the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corporation, which means the federal government insures
each customer's savings up to 100,000 dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
