<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President: Invitation to Turkish Cypriots to Join </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- President Glafcos Clerides
said here Thursday that the Greek Cypriot side's invitation to
the Turkish Cypriots to join the negotiating team for Cyprus'
European Union (EU) membership talks remains open.
</P>
<P>
Clerides made the remarks when he received the credentials of
new head of EU delegation in Cyprus Donato Giovanni Chiarini.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the importance of relations with the EU, he said
that "the road toward accession offers us new possibilities and
new avenues for cooperation between the two communities of
Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
"It is our earnest desire that our Turkish Cypriot compatriots
share with us the task of preparing Cyprus for EU membership," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Clerides extended the invitation to Turkish Cypriots last
March to nominate representatives to join as full members of the
negotiating team for Cyprus' accession.
</P>
<P>
"The efforts of the EU presidency and the European Commission
to convince the Turkish Cypriot community to accept our invitation
did not succeed. The invitation remains in any case, open," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus applied for the full EU membership in 1990. The EU
started accession talks with the Cypriot government in March this
year. The Turkish Cypriot side refused to join the talks.
</P>
<P>
"We firmly believe that the process and prospect of accession
is an important stimulus which should facilitate the efforts of
finding a solution to the political problem which has tormented
my country and its people for so many years," the president said.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that "our primary goal is to find a peaceful
solution to the Cyprus problem based on the bizonal, bicommunal
federation, in accordance with the U.N. resolutions and the High
Level Agreements reached between the two sides in 1977 and 1979."
</P>
<P>
"Membership to the EU is a natural choice, dictated by the
history and culture of the island and constitutes one of the main
pillars of our foreign policy," Clerides noted.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the divided
island in a bizonal, bicommunal federation through peace talks,
but so far no tangible results have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
