<HEADLINE> Germany Leaves Interest Rates on Hold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FRANKFURT, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Germany's central bank, the
Bundesbank, announced Thursday that the country's key interest
rates would remain unchanged as market expectations indicated
earlier.
</P>
<P>
Germany's benchmark discount rate and Lombard rate have been
unchanged at 2.5 percent and 4.5 percent respectively since April
1996. The third key rate, the repurchase rate (repo), has stood at
3.3 percent since October 1997.
</P>
<P>
Many financial experts in Frankfurt had expected that the
Bundesbank would also keep the interest rates on hold until the
transfer of power to the European Central Bank (ECB) in January
next year.
</P>
<P>
In a separate development on Thursday, ECB President Wim
Duisenberg rejected suggestions that the ECB would seek to
establish its credibility by imposing excessively high interest
rates in the single European currency zone.
</P>
<P>
The ECB would be no more restrictive than necessary in terms of
setting interest rates, said Duisenberg at a German bank
conference in Dresden.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ECB chief has called on countries which are due
to launch the single European currency, the euro, next January to
introduce more structural reforms.
</P>
<P>
It was unlikely a stable euro could be maintained in the long
run without a solid financial and economic policy, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
