<HEADLINE> EDS: Updates with president's plans hke091765 --Philippine President Vows to Save Philippine Airlines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada vowed Thursday to do his best to avoid the closure of
Philippine Airlines, saying the shutdown would affect the entire
country.
</P>
<P>
The closure would affect not only the 8,000 employees of the
airlines and their families but also the country, Estrada said
after a late night meeting with the labor union of the airlines.
</P>
<P>
"I will go everything that I can in order to keep Philippine
Airlines going. The fate of thousands of workers rests on this...I
am worried about the thousands of workers who will be affected,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said he will talk with Lucio Tan, the major owner of
the airlines, on Friday to convince the two parties to agree on a
"middle ground" to save the 57-year-old national flag carrier.
</P>
<P>
However, the president is opposed to any government bailout for
the strike-bound firm, Presidential Spokesman Jerry Barican said
earlier Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Airlines announced that the company will close next
Wednesday following the breakdown of talks between the management
and the labor union which represents the pilots and employees who
went on strike in July this year.
</P>
<P>
The airlines has offered the labor union a 20 percent ownership
of the airlines and three seats in the 15-member board of
directors. It also proposed to give each employee 60,000 shares of
stock worth 300,000 pesos (6,849 U.S. dollars at current rate).
</P>
<P>
The union first accepted the proposal, but then reversed its
stand, sending the negotiations to a deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Airlines, born on March 15, 1941, was the first
airlines in Asia. It became the first Asian carrier to fly across
the Pacific in 1946. 
</P>
</TEXT>
