<HEADLINE> Mongolian President Rejects PM Nomination for Sixth Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Mongolian President
Nachagyn Bagabandy on Thursday rejected the ruling union's
nomination of Galsanputsagiin Ganhuyag as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
It is believed to be the sixth time for the president to reject
a nomination since the dismissal of the government led by Prime
Minister Tsakhya Elbegdorj on July 24 as a result of its decision
in May to merge the state-owned Renovation Bank with private
Golomt Bank.
</P>
<P>
A presidential spokesman said that the president did not agree
to submit Ganhuyag's nomination to the Great Hural (parliament)
because he had been prosecuted for twice driving after drinking.
</P>
<P>
The ruling union comprises the Mongolian National Democratic
Party (MNDP) and the Mongolian Social Democratic Party (MSDP).
Ganhuyag is a member of the general committee of the MNDP and the
Great Hural.
</P>
<P>
Ganhuyag's nomination had already been rejected by the
political committee of the MSDP on September 11 for the same
reason as the president.
</P>
<P>
But the MNDP also foiled the MSDP's attempt to present its own
candidate. Later, through consultation between the two parties'
presidents and vice-presidents, the MNDP and the MSDP adopted
Ganhuyag's nomination and wrote to Bagabandy on Tuesday seeking
presidential approval.
</P>
<P>
Under Mongolian law, the ruling union nominates a candidate for
prime minister first and then must consult with the president. If
the president accepts the nomination, he must submit it to the
Great Hural for a vote.
</P>
<P>
The presidential spokesman said that President Bagabandy had
urged the ruling union to nominate a new candidate as early as
possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
