<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Autonomy Bill Passed in Nepal With 7 MPs Injured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Lower House of Nepali
Parliament Thursday passed the crucial Local Autonomy Bill by a
majority after seven opposition MPs were injured in manhandling.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which aims to empower the local bodies, was passed by
voice voting with the support of the ruling Nepali Congress (NC),
the Communist Party of Nepal (Marxism-Leninism, CPN-ML) and the
opposition National Democratic Party (RPP, Chand), which have a
total of 138 MPs in the 205-seat house.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Local Development Keshav Lal Shrestha could not go
to the rostrum to propose the passage of the bill due to the
obstruction of MPs from the opposition Communist Party of Nepal
(United Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML) and RPP (Thapa). He had to do
so in his seat.
</P>
<P>
RPP was split early this year into two groups led respectively
by former prime ministers Lokendra Bahadur Chand and Surya Bahadur
Thapa.
</P>
<P>
MPs from the ruling parties and the opposition began to
manhandle each other when Speaker Ram Chandra Poudel presented the
bill for voting.
</P>
<P>
After the passage of the bill, MPs of the opposition parties
smashed chairs and microphones to vent their anger. They also
smashed the window glass of Speaker Poudel's chamber in the house.
</P>
<P>
Security personnel were mobilized to bring the situation under
control.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-UML claimed at a press conference called later that
seven MPs from it and RPP (Thapa) were injured in the house by the
MPs of ruling parties.
</P>
<P>
It alleged that the bill was passed in an undemocratic way
which was against the parliamentary norms and values.
</P>
<P>
The party said that it would take the issue to the people and
generate awareness about any undemocratic activities of the NC and
the CPN-ML.
</P>
<P>
The NC countercharged in a press release that the behavior of
the opposition MPs was undemocratic and unparliamentary.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-UML demanded that a provision which automatically
terminates one's post if a local elected official defects to
another party be added into the Local Autonomy Bill, tabled in
parliament last week.
</P>
<P>
It fears that if the bill is passed, thousands of local party
workers may defect to the CPN-ML, which broke away from it in
March this year and joined the NC's minority government in late
August.
</P>
<P>
Most of the mayors, deputy mayors, district development
committee chairmen, vice chairmen and members elected from the
CPN-UML during the local elections in May and July last year have
joined the CPN-ML.
</P>
<P>
More local elected members are said to be wishful to join the
CPN-ML, but are waiting for the bill to be passed in parliament.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-UML and RPP (Thapa) had blocked the Lower House
proceedings for four days before Tuesday over the bill.
</P>
<P>
Press reports here said that the NC minority government
submitted an autonomy bill in parliament about five months ago
prohibiting defections at the local level but amended it after the
entry of CPN-ML into the government.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that the CPN-ML aimed to get the bill
passed in order to win over more workers for the local elections
in 11 districts in the mid-western region, which could not take
place last year due to violence and are rescheduled for Friday,
and more importantly, for the general elections due to be held
before November 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Halve Interior Troops by 2001 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Interior
Ministry will cut the number of its troops to 120,000 by 2001,
from the current 250,000, the Interfax news agency reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under a presidential decree and in line with military reform
guidelines to 2005, some 54,000 interior troops will be discharged
by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Sergei Stepashin said his troops, to serve
on contract, would include three mobile groups composed of "four
to five divisions", Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
A slimmer interior force would enable it to concentrate on
civil conflicts within the country, Stepashin said.
</P>
<P>
The reforms also call for the transfer of the penitentiary
system, which employs about 300,000 people, from the Interior
Ministry to the Justice Ministry, Stepashin said.
</P>
<P>
The Justice Ministry has already taken over 731 prisons, 191
detention centers and 63 juvenile correctional centers together
with about one million prisoners and detainees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Photo Show On China's Anti-flood Effort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- An exhibition of
approximately 300 news photos recording China's fight against
severe flooding that has been completed, opened at the China
Revolutionary Museum here today.
</P>
<P>
The works of nearly 100 Chinese journalists and free lancers
depict how Chinese leaders, ordinary Communist Party members,
officers and men of the People's Liberation Army, as well as
civilians joined hands to combat devastating floods in the
middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze and along the Nengjiang
and Songhua rivers in northeast China.
</P>
<P>
There are also some photos showing the civilians' enjoyable,
orderly, and contented life despite the fact that floodwaters
were pounding at river banks and dykes. They were arranged side by
side with other exhibiting photos that depicted how huge floods in
1931 devoured thousands upon thousands of innocent people while
more others went hungry and were practically starving.
</P>
<P>
The photo show will run through September 28 at the joint
sponsorship of the State Flood Control and Drought Relief
Headquarters, Ministry of Water Resources, Xinhua News Agency, the
People's Daily and the Liberation Army News.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
