</P>
<P>
Sahhaf made the remarks following his meeting with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak in his capacity as personal envoy of Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein in the northern coastal city of
Alexandria Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, the Iraqi foreign minister urged the
U.N. to continue dialog with Iraq and then undertake a
comprehensive review of the inspection works as recently proposed
by U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
"Annan's proposal for the comprehensive review for the Iraqi
file is intended to have the U.N. Security Council verify that
Iraq does not any longer possess weapons of mass destruction and
to make it clear that the work has actually been completed,"
Sahhaf said.
</P>
<P>
Arguing that both conditions are "true," he said that "thereby
the embargo on Iraq shall have to be lifted."
</P>
<P>
"The technical details have shown that Iraq had delivered on
its commitments imposed by the U.N. resolutions," he told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Iraq on August 5 decided not to allow U.N. arms inspectors to
visit new sites in Iraq until U.N. Special Commission on Iraq
(UNSCOM), in charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction, was restructured to eliminate American
influence. This has prompted the U.N. to suspend its periodical
review of the U.N. sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions, imposed after Iraq's 1990 invasion of
Kuwait, can be lifted only when the U.N. Security Council is
satisfied that Iraq has eliminated its weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the Security Council would possibly change its recent
decision on suspending the periodical review of the economic
sanctions imposed on Baghdad, Sahhaf gave no direct answer, but
pressed for removing the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
"The sound trend is to seek the lawful explanation of the
U.N. Security Council resolutions and to discuss lifting the ban,"
he said, adding that this is not only an Iraqi demand but also one
sought by the U.N. secretary general.
</P>
<P>
After his meeting with Mubarak, Sahhaf said he updated the
president on the latest developments between Iraq and the U.N. and
their impact on the works of the Security Council and the UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
He also briefed Mubarak on his country's stance in this
connection, which calls for lifting the U.N. sanctions against
Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Lesotho Officers Flee to S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Some senior Lesotho
army officers had fled their country, the South African Press
Association (SAPA) quoted Foreign Affairs Department sources
as saying Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Affairs Department predicted that the fleeing
officers including colonels and lieutenants are likely to
apply for political asylum abroad.
</P>
<P>
Police in Ladybrand, a South African border town, confirmed
earlier in the day that 13 Lesotho officers fled across the
border into South Africa.
</P>
<P>
It is not immediately known why the Lesotho army officers fled
their country.
</P>
<P>
SAPA Thursday also quoted ousted Lesotho Defense Force chief
Lieutenant-General Makhule Mosakheng as saying that he was not
among the officers who had reportedly fled the mountainous kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Mosakheng said that one of the fled officers phoned him from
South Africa, noting that "my impression is that they are not
seeking asylum."
</P>
<P>
The departure of the Lesotho army officers occurred following
reports that South Africa, together with Botswana and Zimbabwe,
are due to release Thursday an investigation report into the
alleged fraud in the Lesotho general elections in May.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho opposition parties reportedly threatened Wednesday
night to reject the report after long expecting the release of
it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
