<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Urges Iran, Afghanistan to Solve Dispute Via </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan called on Iran and
Afghanistan Thursday to take steps to defuse the tension between
them and resolve their differences through talks.
</P>
<P>
"Both sides should move towards each other for reconciliation,"
Foreign Office Spokesman Tariq Altaf told a weekly press briefing.
</P>
<P>
Revoicing Islamabad's concern over the rising tension between
Tehran and Kabul, he said, "there are potential dangers inherent
in the tension between the two Muslim countries."
</P>
<P>
"We believe possible conflict between (Iran and Afghanistan)
will not be in the interest of anyone," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He denied Pakistan's involvement in the Afghan conflict and
said, "our interest lies in the restoration of peace and
tranquillity in Afghanistan."
</P>
<P>
No Pakistani troops or aircraft is in Afghanistan, he said,
adding that such reports were fabricated by "disgruntled elements
who do not want to see the Pakistan-Iran ties to flourish."
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan does not like escalation of tension between
its two neighboring Muslim states for "it involves great risk."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the visit of Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz to
Iran starting Thursday is aimed at defusing the tension between
the two neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
He said Sartaj Aziz will reassure the Iranian authorities of
Pakistan's commitment to the abiding friendship between Pakistan
and Iran, which transcends all vicissitudes.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question about the possibility of mediation
between Iran and the Taliban, he said Pakistan is in touch with
both sides. "We have credibility both in Iran and Afghanistan," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
