<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Market Is Still Free and Open: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong market is still
free, open and well regulated, and the government's incursion in
the market in August was a defense of Hong Kong's economic
interest, Financial Secretary Donald Tsang said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong has long been praised by objective commentators as
the freest market in the world," Tsang told reporters at a
stand-up session at the Central Government Offices.
</P>
<P>
"For that reason, our incursion in the market in August was a
very difficult but serious one," he said, adding that "we were in
the circumstances that we believed we had absolutely no other
option."
</P>
<P>
"We had to defend the linked exchange rate of Hong Kong,
otherwise it would have triggered off another round of devaluation
in the whole of the Asian region and probably greater disasters
outside the region," Tsang added.
</P>
<P>
Tsang's remarks came after the action was criticized by U.S.
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan late Wednesday. Greenspan
said the consequences of the intervention "erode some of the
extraordinary credibility that the Hong Kong Monetary Authority
has achieved."
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong government intervened massively in the stock and
futures markets in August in a bid to squeeze out international
speculators who were engaged in a "double play" in stocks and the
currency.
</P>
<P>
Tsang told reporters that the intervention and the adoption of
a series of follow-up regulatory measures would "help us deal with
speculators more effectively in the future."
</P>
<P>
Tsang reiterated that it was not the government's intention to
sustain the equity of the securities market at any level.
</P>
<P>
"What we had done over the last few weeks have demonstrated
that it is not our intention and that is not our aim at all," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Tsang said he would write to Greenspan explaining the decision,
saying "we have to be very patient about it."
</P>
<P>
"We do understand that from an idealistic position of a free
market, what we did is probably rather exceptional," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tsang himself will leave Hong Kong at the end of September for
a three-week mission to Europe and the United States, reassuring
international business circles of Hong Kong's commitment to free
markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
