<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Time Right for Boosting U.S.-African Trade Ties: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Commerce Secretary
William Daley said Thursday that the time is right for Africa and
the United States to forge a much stronger trade partnership as
the U.S. is developing "an African Commercial Strategy."
</P>
<P>
"American companies are very interested in the continent,"
Daley said at the American Business Association luncheon in the
Kenyan capital.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday, Daley held talks with Kenyan President
Daniel arap Moi on bilateral issues concerning trade, investment,
Kenya's textile exports to the U.S. and the east African state's
privatization process and anti-corruption campaign.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. secretary said that he will visit Nairobi and other
four African capitals in December with the accompany of more than
20 American business leaders.
</P>
<P>
At present, just one percent of American exports goes to the
African market on which the U.S. has only a seven percent share,
far less than Europe.
</P>
<P>
"We can do better. We must do better," said Daley.
</P>
<P>
In response, Kenyan Trade Minister Joseph Kamotho said that he
believes the shifting focus by the United States toward trade and
investment in Africa would create "a very big chance" for further
economic growth of the whole continent.
</P>
<P>
Nairobi was Daley's third and final leg of his four-day
African tour which began Monday. Daley also visited South Africa
and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
This morning, Daley laid a wreath at the site of the August 7
bombing aimed at the U.S. embassy here, which killed some 250
people, including 12 Americans, and wounded nearly 5,000. An
almost simultaneous blast killed 11 Tanzanians at the U.S.
embassy in Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Secretary pledged that Washington will grant
Kenya and Tanzania aid for recovery from the bomb blasts but
failed to reveal more details.
</P>
<P>
Later in the afternoon, the secretary was scheduled to sign a
grant worth three million U.S. Dollars for the Common Market for
Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) over the COMESA region's
peacekeeping and conflict prevention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
