<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Major Policy Bank Expands Lending Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The State Development Bank of
China (SDB) will raise its lending program to more than
150 billion yuan for all of 1998 to help spur national economic
growth, the bank's vice president Yao Zhongmin said here today.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time this year that the policy-oriented bank
has hiked its lending portfolio.
</P>
<P>
The SDB budgeted its annual lendings for 1998 at 95 billion
yuan at the beginning of this year, and then lifted the amount to
122.8 billion yuan some months later.
</P>
<P>
This latest adjustment accounts for about 40 percent of China's
investment in fixed assets this year, Yao said at a meeting on
China's economy and investment environment.
</P>
<P>
He said that the newly increased loans will be mainly used as
matching funds for infrastructure projects financed by money raised
through bond issues by the Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
To increase fiscal spending, the Ministry of Finance earlier
issued 100 billion yuan in special bonds targeting the country's
big-four state-owned commercial banks -- the Industrial and
Commercial Bank of China, the Agricultural Bank of China, the Bank
of China, and the China Construction Bank.
</P>
<P>
Increasing investment, especially in infrastructure facilities,
is an important measure to boost economic growth in China this
year, and that is why the SDB is expanding its lending program,
Yao said.
</P>
<P>
To raise funds, the SDB will issue another 20 to 30 billion yuan
in financial bonds, he added.
</P>
<P>
Bank figures show that the SDB issued 71 billion yuan in loans
in the first half of this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
