<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fireworks Display in HK to Celebrate China's National Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 17 (Xinhua) -- A splendid fireworks
display will light up the sky of Hong Kong's Victoria Harbor on
the night of October 1 to celebrate the 49th anniversary of the
founding of the People's Republic of China, it was announced at a
press conference here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Both the organizers and sponsors of the 23-minute, three-act
show admitted that they also hoped this could bring the local
residents to enjoyment and hope, and boost their confidence at a
time when Hong Kong is suffering from an economic recession.
</P>
<P>
This is the second National Day fireworks display since July 1
last year, when Hong Kong became a special administrative
region of China.
</P>
<P>
"This event shows our commitment to the Hong Kong financial
services industry. We have every confidence that the people of
Hong Kong will continue to work together to maintain Hong Kong's
status as a financial center in the Asia Pacific region," said
Andrew Tang, Associate Director and General Manager of the event's
sponsors, Hong Kong-based financial company Hantec Holdings
Limited.
</P>
<P>
The 22,000 pieces of fireworks to be launched to mid-air are
all from China's mainland and thus have strong Chinese
characteristics, said Christina Ting Yuk-chee, chairman of the
Provisional Urban Council's Entertainment Select Committee. And
the fireworks show will be accompanied by Chinese music which will
be broadcast on local radio to entertain the crowd.
</P>
<P>
The shells will be fired from six barges to be located in a
triangular lay-out in the Victoria Harbor waters so that the
fireworks could be displayed in the air in a pyramid shape,
according to Annie Bentley, Managing Director of Bentley
Communications, the event's promoters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
