<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab World Voice Support for Palestinians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Arab foreign ministers voiced
their support Thursday to the Palestinian stance in the ongoing
negotiations with Israel, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also urged the U.S. to pressure Israel to
implement the agreements it had signed with the Palestinians, the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
They made clear their position at the ongoing 110th session of
the Arab League Ministerial Council in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The direct talks between the Palestinians and Israel, which
began on July 19, have made no headway due to their wide gaps on
security cooperation and the scope of Israeli troops withdrawal
from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians want Israel to accept a U.S. proposal to hand
over 13 percent more of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
But Israel demanded 3 percent be turned into a "nature
reserve," which its has full security control, and required
tougher measures in crackdown on Islamic militants by the
Palestinian National Authority.
</P>
<P>
The council denounced Israel's policy as being based on
"procrastination and maneuvers to impose new facts on the final
status negotiations with the Palestinian party."
</P>
<P>
The final status talks will tackle the thorniest issues in the
Palestinian-Israeli negotiations, including the refugee problem
and the status of Jerusalem, which the Palestinians want to be the
capital of their future state and Israel regards as its eternal
and undivided capital.
</P>
<P>
The council also berated Israel's rejection to restart
negotiations with Syria and Lebanon from where they were left off
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks with Syria came to a stop after Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu came to power and refused to hand back the
occupied Golan Heights as promised by the previous government for
a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon, a close ally of Syria, has insisted on an
unconditional of Israeli troops from its south. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
