<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Wants to Save Philippine Airlines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada is ready to make his best efforts to save the 57-year-old
Philippine Airlines from closing shop, but is opposed to any
government bailout for the strike-bound firm, Presidential
Spokesman Jerry Barican said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think the Philippine government has the money or the
taxpayers have the money, especially under this great economic
hardship, to bail out any large corporation," Barican said.
</P>
<P>
He said the president intends to call officials of the
Employees Association and the management of the airlines to a
meeting in the Presidential Palace "to find out if there is still
a way to save the airlines."
</P>
<P>
However, the necessary steps the president will take do not
include "opening the coffers of the government and using the
hard-earned taxes of the people to bail out the corporation,"
Barican said.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Airlines has announced that it will close on
September 23 following the breakdown of talks between the
management and the pilots and employees who went on strike in July
this year.
</P>
<P>
The management has offered the strikers 20 percent ownership of
the airlines and three seats in the 15-member board of directors.
It also proposed giving 60,000 shares of stock worth 300,000 pesos
(about 6,849 U.S. dollars at current rate) to each employee.
</P>
<P>
The strikers first accepted the proposal, but then reversed
their stand, plunging the negotiations into a deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the airlines' losses caused by the strike and the
burden of cumulative losses over many years have reached at least
2 billion U.S. dollars which are "too heavy for the company to
bear."
</P>
<P>
"Closure is inevitable because this is the only way to preserve
the company's assets to ensure their orderly liquidation and
disposition to creditors and other claimants," the airlines said
in a notice.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Airlines, which first took to the skies on March 15,
1941, was the first airline in Asia. On July 31, 1946, it became
the first Asian carrier to fly across the Pacific. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
