<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers Thursday,
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton Wednesday firmly defended his ability and
intention to lead, saying it was "the right thing" for him to
remain in office despite the furor over his affair with Monica S.
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton's push to quell the global financial
turmoil ran into several obstacles Wednesday as Alan Greenspan,
the Federal Reserve chairman, testified that the world's big
economies had no plans for a coordinated reduction in interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- American and United Nations officials said Wednesday night
there are strong prospects for a Monday meeting that would bring
Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright face to face with Iranian
Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi. It would be the highest level of
contact between the estranged governments since the hostage crisis
of 1979.
</P>
<P>
-- Texas governor George W. Bush, son of former president
George Bush, said the scandal involving President Clinton is
depressing and has left him wondering if he wants to seek the
presidency. He is a possible candidate for the Republican
nomination in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- Russia's new government said it may revise the terms of a 40
billion domestic debt restructuring, a move that could help mend
the country's relations with international investors.
</P>
<P>
-- The International Monetary Fund opened negotiations with
Brazil over what could become a multi-billion-dollar rescue
package. The two sides haven't agreed on the reforms Brazil would
have to adopt to qualify. 
