<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Recession in Japan Dampens German Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 17 (Xinhua) -- German exports to Japan dropped
by 11.7 percent in the first half of this year, mainly because of
Japan's recession and the weak Japanese Yen, the German Federal
Statistics Office said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The data showed that exports to Japan in the first half year
fell to 9.2 billion marks (5.4 billion U.S. dollars), while
imports from Japan increased by 17.4 percent to 20.8 billion marks
(12.3 billion dollars), leading through to a trade deficit of 11.6
billion marks (6.9 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, Japan remained the second largest trading partner of
Germany, following the United States. It bought 1.9 percent of
Germany's total exports and 5.1 percent of Germany's total imports
came from Japan, the statistics office said.
</P>
<P>
It was also estimated that Germany's trade deficit with Japan
for 1998 could reach the highest level since 1992 when the deficit
was 23.3 billion marks (13.8 billion dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
