<HEADLINE> Malaysia Bars Entry of Singapore Air Force Planes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Air Force
planes will be barred from entering Malaysia's air space from
Friday, Malaysian Defense Minister Syed Hamid Albar announced
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
All special arrangements and waivers now granted to Singapore
air force planes to use the Malaysian air space would be
withdrawn, he said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's decision was taken in view of the increasing
congestion over the country's air space and concerns expressed by
the general public, the defense minister said.
</P>
<P>
"It is not an easy decision...it was taken in the best interest
of Malaysia," Malaysia's national news agency Bernama quoted him
as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, he said Singapore air force planes wishing to use
Malaysian air space from Friday would have to apply for individual
clearance from the Malaysian authorities and it would be up to
Malaysia to grant such clearance.
</P>
<P>
At present, Singapore air force planes are given several types
of special waivers from applying for such clearance and normally a
blanket clearance was given, he said.
</P>
<P>
The defense minister said the Singapore government was informed
of the decision through its High Commission here Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
It was noted that Malaysia's decision was taken after Singapore
Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew's memoirs was published, which was
alleged to contain critical remarks about Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Over the last few days, several Malaysian leaders including
Syed Hamid have criticized Lee.
</P>
<P>
But Syed Hamid said the decision was based on security reasons
and the country's interest and was not a reaction to the critical
remarks about Malaysia in Lee's memoirs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
