<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt, Iraq Hold Trade-Booster Meeting in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Joint Egyptian-Iraqi
Committee will convene here in November under the co-chairmanship
of trade ministers from both countries, aiming to shore up trade
and economic ties.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Middle East News Agency Thursday,
Chairman of the Egyptian Trade Office in Baghdad Ahmed Hosni said
the committee meeting was agreed upon by Egyptian Trade Minister
Ahmed Goweili and his Iraqi counterpart Mohamed Mahdi Saleh.
</P>
<P>
The committee is to study ways to enhance bilateral trade
relations in the light of a memo of understanding reached by the
two sides in June, he added.
</P>
<P>
Ahead of the gathering in Cairo, Egypt will take part in
Baghdad International Exhibition to be staged on November 1-10.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian exports to Iraq under the U.N.-Iraq oil-for-food
program stood at 230 million dollars during the period from
January till the end of August, according to the chairman of the
Egyptian Trade office in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Cairo and Baghdad have witnessed noticeable
improvement recently when high level visits were exchanged.
</P>
<P>
Goweili paid a visit to Iraq in June to attend the inauguration
of the Egyptian Products Exhibition and signed with his Iraqi
counterpart Saleh a memo of understanding for bilateral economic
and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Health Minister Ismail Sallam visited Baghdad last
month leading a medical team during which they operated on some
Iraqi patients.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the official interaction, some Egyptian firms
have been doing a robust business with Baghdad, exporting food,
medicine, and other daily necessities, while others have offered
to participate in schemes to develop Iraq's dilapidated oil
facilities and prospect for new fields.
</P>
<P>
Under the Iraq-U.N. oil-for-food deal struck in 1996, Iraq is
allowed to sell a limited amount of oil every six months to import
food, medicine and other humanitarian supplies.
</P>
<P>
The program is an exception of the crippling economic sanctions
the U.N. Security Council imposed on Iraq after its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
