<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Enjoys Payments Surplus under Current, Capital Accounts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- China continues to have an
international payments surplus under both current and capital
accounts, allowing its currency to remain stable.
</P>
<P>
Wu Xiaoling, director of the State Administration of Foreign
Exchange, said at an international seminar called "China's
Economic and Investment Perspective" held in Beijing today that
China's decision to maintain a stable exchange rate is not a
political commitment.
</P>
<P>
She said it is based on the country's international payments
and its own interests. Moreover, it is an international
obligation that China shoulders.
</P>
<P>
Though the Asian financial crisis exerts great pressure on
China's exports, Chinese products are still quite competitive on
the international market, she added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Wu predicted that China will not have a trade
deficit under its capital account this year because direct
investment constitutes a majority of the funds coming from abroad.
</P>
<P>
China, with a market of 1.2 billion people and political
stability, will be able to absorb even more investment from other
countries in the future, she said.
</P>
<P>
China has adopted a positive attitude toward investment by
transnational companies, and increased investment from Europe and
the Unites States will counteract a decline of investment from
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
She said that a pressing task for China at present is to
prevent and clamp down on the illegal flow of foreign exchange. A
certain amount of foreign exchange has gone to other countries
beginning last April after China cut interest rates on the yuan
twice in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has taken a series of measures to insure
its development is adaptable to the new international situation
which has arisen since the start of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, China is working to improve management of the
resettlement and sale of foreign exchange to increase its foreign
exchange reserve.
</P>
<P>
China will also distinguish foreign-exchange revenue and
expenditure under the current account from that under the capital
account, keeping strict tabs on the latter to ensure the legal
flow of foreign exchange and crack down on illegal exchanges.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
