<HEADLINE> EDS: Updates with details of talks hke091753 --Philippine Airlines Shuts Down After Talks Break Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Airlines, the
national commercial flag carrier, announced here Thursday that it
would close effective midnight of September 23 following the
breakdown of talks between the management and the labor union.
</P>
<P>
The airlines said that the closure was recommended by the
Interim Receivership Committee to the airlines' board of
directors, which then approved the measure during an emergency
closed-door meeting Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The company said the management exhausted all efforts to keep
it operational pending the outcome of the negotiations with the
labor union who represents the pilots and employees who went on
strike in July this year.
</P>
<P>
The burden of cumulative losses over many years and the losses
caused by the strike during the ongoing Asian financial crisis
have run into billions of pesos and become too heavy for the
company to bear, the airlines said.
</P>
<P>
It added that it apologizes to all its passengers and customs
who are most affected by the closure and advises the riding public
to make necessary alternative arrangements to minimize the
inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Airlines, which first took to the skies on March 15,
1941, was the first airline in Asia. On July 31, 1946, it became
the first Asian carrier to fly across the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
The closure ends the airlines' 57 and a half years of service
to the nation during which it contributed significantly to the
national development and unity, the airlines said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
