<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines Management Issues Notice of  Closure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The management of Philippine
Airlines issued here Thursday a notice of closure of the airlines
after the management and the labor union failed to reach an
acceptable arrangement to keep it operational.
</P>
<P>
"We are deeply saddened to announce that on September 23, 1998,
Philippine Airlines will close following the breakdown of
negotiations between the management and the airlines' labor union
to forge an acceptable arrangement to ensure continuing industrial
peace," the notice said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the management has exhausted all efforts to keep
the company operational pending the outcome of its negotiations
with the labor union, which represents the pilots and employees
who went on strike in July this year.
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, the insurmountable burden of continued losses
has become too heavy for the company to bear. With no fresh
capital infusion, the company can not operate viably in the face
of enormous losses and the harsh business environment," the notice
said.
</P>
<P>
According to press reports, the debt the airlines has
accumulated over the past 57 years has run into at least two
billion U.S. dollars. As a result of the losses and the ongoing
Asian financial crisis, the airlines downsized its domestic and
international flights and laid off some 5,000 employees and
pilots.
</P>
<P>
The airlines apologizes to all its passengers and customs who
are most affected by the closure, advising the riding public to
make necessary alternative arrangements to minimize the
inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
"We appreciate your understanding and patience during this
difficult period. Closure is inevitable because this is the only
way to preserve the company's assets to ensure their orderly
liquidation and disposition to creditors and other claimants. We
urging our riding public to make the necessary alternative travel
arrangements," the notice said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the airlines said the Interim Receivership Committee
sent to the airlines by the government recommended the closure to
the board of directors, which then approved it during an emergency
closed-door meeting Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Airlines, which first took to the skies on March 15,
1941, was the first airline in Asia. On July 31, 1946, it became
the first Asian carrier to fly cross the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
The closure ends the airlines' 57 and a half years of service
to the nation during which it contributed significantly to the
national development and unity, the airlines said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
