<HEADLINE> Five-year Plan formulated in Nigeria to Eradicate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government is
resolved to eradicate vaccine preventable diseases suffered by
children, especially poliomyelitis, under a five-year action
plan.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Health Minister Debo Adeyemi said recently that a
successful implementation of the plan would save thousands of
children in the country, The Guardian reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
More than one million children in Nigeria reportedly die each
year from vaccine preventable diseases with poliomyelitis maiming
thousands of Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
The 1999-2003 plan focuses on the eradication of
poliomyelitis, the strengthening of the routine immunization
services and the increased surveillance of childhood killer
diseases.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing in capital Abuja, marking this year's
National Immunization Days (NID), the minister said that the
priority of health care is to achieve total eradication of
poliomyelitis in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Adeyemi announced that two rounds of vaccination have planned
for this year and that the first round is scheduled for November 4
and 5 and the second round will be on December 9 and 10.
</P>
<P>
The minister called on health commissioners in all states to
ensure that all print and electronic media in the country are
mobilized and committed to publishing 1998 NIDs information,
especially in rural areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
