<HEADLINE> Indonesia Opens Women's Crisis Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian Women's Crisis
Center was officially opened by first lady Hasri Ainun Habibie
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In her speech, Ainun expressed the hope that the center would
be able to help solve cases of violence against women.
</P>
<P>
She said harassment against women, occurring both at home and
in their places of work, are rarely exposed.
</P>
<P>
"Sometimes the women could do nothing but to let them happen.
The victims could not find the right solutions either," she said,
adding that problems faced by women should not be disregarded as
they affect practically half of the Indonesian population.
</P>
<P>
Ainun said it would be better to prevent the damage from being
done than to start a healing process after the damage is done.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the Indonesian Women for Development Kemala said the
crisis center was formed to address the rising incidence of
harassment against women.
</P>
<P>
The crisis center will tackle sexual harassment cases, marriage
problems, and the protection of women's rights, Kemala added.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, Women's Affairs Minister Tuti Alawiyah
urged the country's women organizations to sit together and seek
solutions to problems that women face. 
</P>
</TEXT>
