<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, U.S. Still Differ on CTBT: Jashwant Singh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 17 (Xinhua) -- An Indian senior official
said Thursday that India and the United States still have
different perceptions over the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty
(CTBT).
</P>
<P>
Addressing the economic editors' conference here, Planning
Commission Deputy Chairman Jaswant Singh, who is also the special
emissary of the prime minister, said that he would strive to
narrow the gap when he again meet U.S. Assistant Secretary of
State Strobe Tolbott in Washington next week.
</P>
<P>
Jaswant Singh and Strobe Tolbott has held four rounds of talks
since June 11 this year over India's nuclear tests conducted in
May 1998 and CTBT. It was reported that the United States has time
and again urged India to stop nuclear development programme and
sign CTBT with no conditions. India, however, has insisted that it
would not stop its nuclear development programme and it should
have a minimum nuclear deterrence. Furthermore, it wants the
United States to recognize its de facto nuclear power state, lift
its economic sanctions imposed on it following its nuclear tests
and agree to transfer advanced technology to India if it wants
India to sign CTBT.
</P>
<P>
Jaswant Singh refused to give any details of the his several
talks with Tolbott on CTBT issue. He said that he was committed
not to reveal the outcome of his secret talks with Tolbott.
</P>
<P>
Indian Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee said Wednesday that
India would not sign the CTBT in its present discriminatory form.
"We would like some changes to be made, particularly regarding
transfer of high technology. We are having talks on this and other
points," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I know the treaty itself is not going to be amended, but
certain other arrangements should be made to create conditions for
India to sign CTBT," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
