<HEADLINE> Jordan's National Carrier on Privatization Track </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's debt-ridden national
carrier, the Royal Jordanian (RJ), has pinned financial and legal
advisors for its privatization, sources from the RJ said.
</P>
<P>
The RJ has initialed preliminary agreements with France's Bank
Paribas and the international Clifford Chance company to authorize
them to deal with the financial and legal affairs in restructuring
and stakes sale, the Jordan Times newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian government has decided to implement a World
Bank-prescribed blueprint to privatize the RJ and Bank Paribas
will help evaluate the airline's assets, restructure its balance
sheet and recommend ways to handle its debts, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The RJ is straddled with 700 million Jordanian dinars (about
990 million U.S. dollars) of debts, due to years of mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
The bank will eventually market the main parts of the RJ,
including the aviation and technical support sectors, said the
sources. The remaining duty-free shops, engineering and catering
services will be run by a state-owned company.
</P>
<P>
The Clifford Chance will help improve management in the RJ,
make clear the RJ's legal liabilities and establish reasonable
relationship between the RJ and the Civil Aviation Authorities,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank will fund part of the financial and legal work,
they added.
</P>
<P>
Privatization of the RJ is part of a government campaign,
launched in 1989, to tap the potential of the private sector, draw
foreign investment and finally streamline and privatize
large-scale public companies.
</P>
<P>
The plan met strong opposition from the parliament and has not
been legalized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
