<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Lower on Renewed Weakness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Renewed weakness in the
Japanese yen against the U.S. dollar weighed on the Australian
dollar Thursday and pushed it to a sub 59.00 U.S. cents close for
the first time in a week.
</P>
<P>
The local currency was undermined by large U.S. investor
selling overnight in the wake of U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan's testimony.
</P>
<P>
Strength in the U.S. dollar, also a result of Greenspan's
speech, shoved the Japanese yen down which in turn damaged the
Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed here at 58.97 U.S. cents from
59.61.
</P>
<P>
"This morning we saw a bit of a sell down from 59.30 towards
59.00 on the back of the weaker yen," St. George Bank manager of
foreign exchange trading Stuart Moore said.
</P>
<P>
"Last night Greenspan came out and said that the G-7 (Group of
Seven) won't be moving towards a coordinated rate cut and that put
the U.S. dollar under a bit of support and the Aussie under a bit
of pressure," he said.
</P>
<P>
In his testimony to a committee of the House of
Representatives, Greenspan said there was no intention, at
present, to make a coordinated G-7 interest rate cut.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said weakness in the gold price and commodity prices
had also adversely impacted on the traditionally commodity-driven
currency.
</P>
<P>
Moore said he believed there was support for the Australian
dollar at these low levels and it was likely the currency would
bounce in offshore overnight trade.
</P>
<P>
"Right at this stage I think we might bounce a bit, but in the
next week or so I think the Aussie has some risk of downside," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the domestic currency could fall as far as 58.20 U.S.
cents.
</P>
<P>
At the close here the local currency was trading at 79.34
Japanese yen from 80.05 and 0.9944 German marks from 1.0091.
</P>
</TEXT>
