<HEADLINE> Jordan's Water Pollution Inquiry to Be Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The investigation of a water
pollution scandal which in part led to the resignation of Jordan's
last government, will be over in two weeks, the prosecutor in
charge said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mohammad Harahsheh, who led the probe, confirmed that seven
government employees in connection with the water incident have
been arrested.
</P>
<P>
"Investigation proved they were involved in the water crisis
and they were arrested for further investigation," he said.
</P>
<P>
The prosecutor did not rule out more arrests with the deepening
of the probe.
</P>
<P>
Those proved responsible will be prosecuted when the
investigation ends, the semi-official Jordan Times newspaper
quoted Harahsheh as saying.
</P>
<P>
Two of the detained were officials taking charge of quality
control and laboratory affairs in water departments and the other
five were from the Zai Water Treatment Plant.
</P>
<P>
The water plant, which supplies most of Amman's running water,
is believed to be the source of contamination for a whole week in
July.
</P>
<P>
In early July, extra algae were spotted in the water of the
Zai plant, but it failed to make efforts to reduce the volume of
water passing through the filters, nor did it increase the carbon
used to treat the algae.
</P>
<P>
The residents in west Amman soon complained that the water
flowing out of their taps had an odor and contained worms, and a
number of citizens were hospitalized for diarrhea and
nausea-related diseases in the subsequent weeks.
</P>
<P>
Though part of the plant was closed shortly after the incident,
the water scandal stirred a political storm in Jordan, which
forced the resignation of the whole cabinet, led by former Prime
Minister Abdul-Salam Majali. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
