<HEADLINE> Indian, Pakistani Troops Exchange Fire in Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Indian and Pakistani border
troops Wednesday exchanged heavy artillery and mortar fire in
Kargil sector of Jammu and Kashmir, the long-standing disputed
area between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The exchange of shelling continued for at least three hours
from 1600 (local time) Wednesday, a Defense Ministry spokesman
said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Three barracks on the Indian side suffered extensive damage in
the cross-border firing on the outskirts of Kargil, but there was
no report of any casualty as troops had already taken positions at
safer areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman did not give any reason for the new exchange of
fire between India and Pakistan. Since this year, especially after
the nuclear tests conducted by the two countries in May, more and
heavier exchanges of fire between the two sides' border troops
have been reported.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have fought three wars since 1947 and two out
of them were over Kashmir. India maintains that Kashmir is an
integrate part of its territory while Pakistan insists that it is
a disputed area. Because of their big difference over the issue,
they have failed to reach any agreement so far through various
talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
