<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court's New Measures to Curb Judicial Corruption (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- In order to maintain justice
and strengthen internal supervision, China's Supreme Court today
issued regulations on disciplinary penalties for court personnel,
and decided to appoint supervisors for the lower courts.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Mingshan, vice-president of the Supreme People's Court,
revealed the two measures to the press here today.
</P>
<P>
"These moves are concrete steps by the Supreme Court in
implementing top-legislator Li Peng's directive on the ongoing
judiciary shake-up," Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
Li, chairman of the National People's Congress Standing
Committee, said yesterday that "the violation of regulations in
the profession, and the neglect of work ethics by some officials
in judicial departments, are so serious that it has endangered
fair trial and posed a threat to social stability, and must be
halted immediately."
</P>
<P>
He warned judicial bodies not to take the "educational
rectification campaign" as a temporary movement, but to further it
by formulating relevant rules and set up new codes of conducts for
law enforcement personnels.
</P>
<P>
The methods of court discipline spelled-out 48 activities by
court personnel that are punishable by disciplinary warning,
demerits, demotion, dismissal from judgeship or expulsion from
judicial departments.
</P>
<P>
These activities include accepting offer of money, gift or
dinners from litigants, secretely handling lawsuits without
complying with legal procedures or refusing to open a trial that
should be opened, introducing lawyers to litigants or privately
meeting with a litigant and his attorney.
</P>
<P>
An on-duty intoxicated judge may be dismissed from office if
"serious consequences occur," according to the methods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
