<HEADLINE> Australian Stock Market Drifts Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
drifted lower Thursday as investors remained on the sidelines
while key global economic and political matters remained
unresolved.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index dropped 10.4 points to 2542.8, with
national turnover figures showing just 249.31 million shares
traded at a value of only 670.88 million Australian dollars
(395.81 million U.S. dollars), with 517 falls, 420 rises and 396
steady.
</P>
<P>
Brett O'Donovan from Henderson Charlton Jones said some of
Thursday's fall could be attributed to a drop in Japan, but mostly
it was due to lack of buying interest.
</P>
<P>
He said a minor fall on Wall Street overnight was not enough to
bring activity into the local market.
</P>
<P>
"Investors just aren't looking at this low volatility at the
moment, it virtually means nothing in the context of what we have
seen in the past few months," O'Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
The lack of clear direction on interest rates and the
continuation of the local election campaign were seen as
contributors to buying hesitancy.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index fell 12.6 points to 4471.3, with
banking and insurance stocks generally firmer.
</P>
<P>
ANZ got some support from bargain hunters after its steady
decline since May, adding 11 cents. Of the other major banks,
National Australia was down 17.6 cents, Commonwealth fell 1.5 and
Westpac finished 8.9 cents down.
</P>
<P>
In the insurance sector, major AMP lost 18.1 cents while its
takeover target GIO was up five cents.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications major Telstra was down two cents, while the
shares of media giant News Corp lost six and its preferred shares
closed down 12 cents.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index fell 9.7 points to 986.4, with mining
stocks markedly weaker.
</P>
<P>
Resources heavyweight BHP was down 23.8 cents, Rio Tinto fell
three.The gold index was 8.6 points lower at 1000.2 as the
bullion price slipped 2.05 per ounce to 287.05 U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
