<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Bank Rules out Possibility of Interest Rate Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking official of
China's central bank today ruled out the possibility of an
interest rate cut in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Liu Mingkang, vice governor of the People's Bank of China, told
an international seminar on China's economy and investment
prospects which opened here today, that there is little room for a
rate cut considering the present rate level.
</P>
<P>
He told the meeting that the Chinese government has cut
interest rates twice this year after concluding that real interest
rates had been too high.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the growth rate of the broad money supply is
approaching the 16 percent level set by the central bank, while
the increase of the narrow money supply is also expected to
rebound in the future.
</P>
<P>
According to Liu, the country's economy is going in the
direction of the set macro-control target, with the growth of
fix-assets investment to exceed 15 percent for the year,
which will play a big role in boosting the general economy.
</P>
<P>
He expects the country's commodity price index to soon return
to a normal level from the present negative growth, which will
trigger changes in the real interest rate level.
</P>
<P>
The vice governor believes the government must take into
consideration the exchange rate factor when formulating interest
rate policies in order to avoid the pressure of big interest
rate drops on the exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
At present, the nominal rate for one-year savings deposits
stands at 4.77 percent. In August, the national retail price index
dropped 3.3 percent on a year-on-year basis, making the real
interest rate level higher than eight percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Recession in Japan Dampens German Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Germany' exports to Japan
dropped by 11.7 percent in the first half of this year, mainly due
to Japan's recession and a weak Japanese Yen, the German Federal
Statistics Office said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Latest data released by the office showed that Germany's
exports to Japan in the first half year dropped to 9.2 billion
marks (about 5.4 billion U.S. dollars), while imports from Japan
rose by 17.4 percent to 20.8 billion marks (about 12.3 billion
dollars), with a trade deficit of 11.6 billion marks (about 6.9
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Japan remained Germany's second largest trading
partner after the United States, absorbing 1.9 percent of German
exports worldwide and accounting for 5.1 percent of Germany's
total import value, the statistics office said.
</P>
<P>
It also estimated that Germany's trade deficit with Japan for
the whole year could surge to the highest level registered since
1992 when the deficit ran up to 23.3 billion marks (about 13.8
billion dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
