<HEADLINE> U.S. Urged to Keep Commitment on Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government should
keep their commitment on Tibet and not do anything that interferes
in China's internal affairs or hurts Chinese feeling.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao made the remark
here this afternoon in response to a media report.
</P>
<P>
It has been reported that the United States provided various
forms of aid to Tibetan splittists in India and that this support
is still going on.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that Tibet, an autonomous region of China, is an
inalienable part of the Chinese territories.
</P>
<P>
"The Tibet issue is a pure internal affair of China and the
Chinese government and people oppose any attempt from foreign
force to interfere in the country's internal affairs by putting a
hand in Tibet," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government has time and again reaffirmed that Tibet is
part of China and the United States does not support the
"independence" of Tibet, the spokesman pointed out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
