<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Meeting Commemorates Indian Medical Relief Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- A meeting to commemorate the
60th anniversary of an Indian Medical Relief Mission to China in
1938 was held here today at the sponsorship of the Chinese
People's Association for Friendship with Foreign Countries
(CPAFFC).
</P>
<P>
CPAFFC Vice-President Su Guang and Indian Ambassador Vijay
Kunhinandan Nambiar presided over the ceremony. Family members and
friends of Dr. Dwarkanath Kotnis, a member of the mission,
attended the event.
</P>
<P>
The team of five doctors, including Dr. Kotnis, arrived in
China in 1938 during the War of Resistance to Japanese
Aggression. Dr. Kotnis worked as a surgeon in Eighth Route Army
hospitals in Yan'an and northern China.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Kotnis joined the Communist Party of China in 1942 and
later served as president of the Bethune International Peace
Hospital following the death of Dr. Norman Bethune. Dr. Kotnis
died of an unspecified illness while working in China.
</P>
<P>
Su noted that China and India are major powers which face
common responsibilities for safeguarding world peace and promoting
economic growth. He also expressed China's desire to further
develop friendly relations with its close neighbor.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Nambiar presented a moving speech which he concluded
in Chinese.
</P>
<P>
"The Indian Medical Relief Mission to China fully displayed the
enthusiasm and earnest desire of the people of both nations to
develop good relations. We have unremittingly pursued further and
better bilateral relations based on mutual understanding and
respect.
</P>
<P>
"Friendly Sino-Indian ties will be a key for ensuring peace and
stability of the region, Asia and the world as a whole," Nambiar
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
