<HEADLINE> Australian PM Demands Apology From State-funded Media </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister
John Howard Thursday accused Australia's state-owned broadcaster
of having a bias against his government and demanded an apology
over his treatment by its interviewer.
</P>
<P>
Simmering tension in the ruling Australian Liberal Party and
National Party coalition over the Australian Broadcasting
Corporation's (ABC's) election campaign coverage boiled over when
Howard appeared on Perth ABC Radio.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister reminded interviewer Verity James that the
ABC had a responsibility to provide balanced political coverage in
an election.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister was quoted Thursday by the Australian
Associated Press as saying the ABC's coverage of this election
campaign has not been balanced.
</P>
<P>
Howard and the interviewer had some sharp exchanges over the
Liberal Party's decision to accept cigarette sponsorship of its
federal conference and whether he was stressed by the campaign.
</P>
<P>
But the real fireworks began when James asked a question which
wrongly implied the opposition party, the Australian Labor Party,
had suggested that the government's tax reforms would make heroin
cheaper.
</P>
<P>
"Is it cheaper under a GST (goods and services tax), or is it
just cheaper?" she asked.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister pins his election victory on public
acceptance of his taxation reform plan, of which 10 percent GST is
the central piece.
</P>
<P>
Howard was clearly angered by the question, which came shortly
before he was abruptly cut off for a morning news bulletin, the
AAP reported.
</P>
<P>
James promised to clear up the confusion over the question
before the bulletin but did not do so.
</P>
<P>
Howard's advisers and ABC staff exchanged heated words as soon
as the interview finished.
</P>
<P>
"I thought it was a very odd line of questioning," he later
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"The suggestion that in some way the GST is linked to heroin is
about the most bizarre thing I've heard."
</P>
<P>
"I want an apology from the ABC without qualification, and I
expect to get it."
</P>
<P>
The AAP said Howard's ruling party and the ABC have been waging
a behind-the-scene battle about election coverage over the past
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Howard camp has claimed that their policy launches are
going largely ignored by ABC Television while many of its
mid-evening newsbreaks make no mention of the election.
</P>
<P>
Government figures claimed their complaints were justified this
week when the conservative Institute of Public Affairs released an
analysis of TV news coverage showing ABC reports were four times
more critical of the coalition than of Labor.
</P>
<P>
Caught up in the furor is the issue of ABC funding. The
government made a deep cut into the ABC funding soon after the
last election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Tumble in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices plunged in Tokyo
Thursday as the Japanese government's efforts to fix the Long-Term
Credit Bank of Japan (LTCB) failed to erase worries over the
country's ailing financial system and weakening economy.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 338.56 points, or 2.38
percent, from Wednesday's close to end at 13,859.14.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, declined 18.44 points or 1.70 percent to
1,069.06.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went slightly up to an estimated
410 million shares from Wednesday's 385.94 million shares.
</P>
<P>
The LTCB was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
With the exception of telecommunications, all 33 TOPIX sectors
declined as a broad range of issues fell to their lowest levels
ever.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei advanced nearly 100 points in the early going and
traders suspected that George Soros, the high-profile hedge fund
manager, has begun to actively buy back Japanese shares.
</P>
<P>
Those gains, however, were wiped clean by the end of the
morning session and shares fell throughout the afternoon as
investors groped for a reason to buy, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,341 issues listed on the First Section, losers
surpassed gainers 912 to 239, with 130 issues remaining
unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
