<HEADLINE> Sam Rainsy Party Agrees to Join Assembly Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SIEM REAP, Cambodia, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's main
opposition political party leader Sam Rainsy said Thursday that
his party would not boycott the convention of a new parliament and
the three-party summit hosted by King Norodom Sihanouk.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with King Sihanouk here, Sam Rainsy told
reporters that the Sam Rainsy Party (SRP) supported the king to
host the summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
He, who described his four-hour audience with the king as
"cordial and satisfactory", believed that the king can play an
important role as a coordinator.
</P>
<P>
"But we did not touch upon the formation of the new
government," Sam Rainsy added.
</P>
<P>
Sam Rainsy said he places great hopes on the summit meeting. If
agreement can be reached among the three parties, the situation in
Cambodia will return to normal.
</P>
<P>
According to a communique released by Royal Palace Thursday
morning, the three-party summit meeting is set on September 22 in
Siem Reap and the National Assembly will be convened on September
24. Then the members of parliament will go to the famous Angkor
Wat temple nearby to be sworn in.
</P>
<P>
So far, the three main party leaders have all agreed to
participate in the summit meeting. They are Chea Sim and Hun Sen,
President and vice President of the Cambodian People's Party,
Prince Ranariddh, president of the Funcinpec party and Sam Rainsy
of the SRP.
</P>
<P>
Although the SRP is a small party in parliament, which
could not resist other two main parties in principle, "we will
stick to the election complaints and seek a fair resolution of
them. I will also ask to discuss the civil rights at the meeting
such as the freedom of movement of opposition leaders and members
of Parliament which is banned by the government," Sam Rainsy said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sam Rainsy expressed his concerns that if the current
crisis cannot be solved satisfactorily, the protesters will go to
the street again.
</P>
<P>
The two main opposition parties -- the Funcinpec party and the
SRP -- have been protesting against July 26 "election violations."
At least two people have been killed in clashes with the police
and many more injured since the government clamped down on
unauthorized protests in September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
