<HEADLINE> Thai-Myanmar Border Trade Resumes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Mae Sot-Myawaddy
checkpoint and Thai-Myanmar Friendship Bridge at the Thai-Myanmar
border have reopened after nine months of closure, a Thai commerce
official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The reopening coincided with the launching of Myawaddy's
one-stop facility for trade, customs and immigration, said the
official who refused to be named.
</P>
<P>
Col Min Hla Aung, head of Myanmar's Border Trade Department,
presided over the opening ceremony Wednesday, with the
participation of Thai officials.
</P>
<P>
After the ceremony, Thai and Myanmar officials discussed trade
at a meeting co-chaired by Min Hla Aung and Chatchaval
Sukijvanich, deputy permanent secretary at the Thai Commerce
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Chatchaval proposed the establishment of a Thai-Myanmar border
trade coordinating agency to meet at least three times a year.
</P>
<P>
The Thai side also proposed that Myanmar lift an import ban on
cattle, jewelry, wood products and marine animals.
</P>
<P>
The ban had led to the smuggling of cattle from Thailand to
Myanmar and both countries had lost revenue for 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
