<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Egyptian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Egyptian newspapers on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Al-Ahram:
</P>
<P>
-- Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat and
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak met Wednesday and reviewed the
impediments in Palestinian-Israeli peace talks in view of the
failure of U.S. Mideast Peace Coordinator Dennis Ross to achieve a
breakthrough in his current Mideast mission.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak stressed the importance of attaining a good agreement
and Arafat called on the world to support the proclamation of a
Palestinian state in May 1999.
</P>
<P>
Al-Akhbar:
</P>
<P>
-- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa and his French
counterpart Hubert Vedrine will meet next week in New York on the
sidelines of the U.N. General Assembly to review the statement
made by the Egyptian-French working group on an international
conference.
</P>
<P>
The international conference, which was envisaged in an
Egyptian-French initiative put forward in May, aims to salvage the
faltering Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
The working group held its first official meeting Monday and
formulated a two-phase plan for the conference, with the first
phase involving countries that are indirectly related to the peace
talks and the second involving those parties directly concerned.
</P>
<P>
Al Gomhuria:
</P>
<P>
-- Arab foreign ministers urged the international community to
impose appropriate sanctions on Israel, whose policies jeopardize
regional and international peace, until it complies with the
international legitimacy and abides by the signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
The call was made in a draft resolution at the 110th session of
the Arab League Ministerial Council meeting, which opened in Cairo
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Gazette:
</P>
<P>
-- Minister of Housing and Reconstruction Mohamed Ibrahim
Soliman said that 1.5 million flats were constructed for low
income bracket against 90,000 luxurious housing units from 1982 to
1995.
</P>
<P>
The youth can get flats by paying for only 60 percent of their
cost, Soliman said, and 6,000 apartment house will be built to
contain 30 million people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
