<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 17 (Xinhua)-- President Laurent Kabila said
government forces were massing to attack rebel-held towns in the
east of the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
Adressing a rally of about 30,000 people in Kinshasa on
Wednesday, Kabila that despite the war, Congo would go to the
polls next year as planned, said a report reaching here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kabila called on Kinshasa residents to form civil defence groups
that would be given arms to wage a "people's war" against rebels
and their backers to create a peaceful atmosphere for elections.
</P>
<P>
"Don't forget that the Ugandans are still in Kisangani and
Bunia (in the northeast), and in the east the Rwandans are in
Goma and Bukavu," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But all these towns are being encircled and our forces are
massing up. The local inhabitants, who are following the example
of Kinshasa are arming themselves to take on the enemy," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Kabila accused neighboring Rwanda and Uganda of invading in
support of the rebels, but both countries deny direct
involvement. Uganda said it had troops in Congo but only to fight
Ugandan rebels operating from there.
</P>
<P>
Tutsi-led rebels, who took up arms on August 2 in a bid to
topple Kabila, hold a vast swathe of eastern Congo including the
towns of Uvira, Bukavu and Goma.
</P>
<P>
Kabila said 25,000 youths in Kinshasa alone had been recruited
into the army for a planned counter-attack in the east.
</P>
<P>
Angola, Zimbabwe and Namibia have sent troops to fight
alongside Kabila's forces. The allies have routed the rebels in
the west, driving them out of the towns they held there.
</P>
<P>
Aid workers reported signs of a continuing loyalist
buildup in the central twon of Kindu, the likely springboard for
a push for Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, rebel commander Jonas Padiri said that at
kabila's request hutu fighters from neighbouring burundi had
joined in the war.
</P>
<P>
So far efforts by regional leaders to broker a ceasefire in
the conflict have ended in failure, largely over Kabila's refusal
to meet the rebels and insistence that Rwanda and Uganda first
withdraw their troops.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aged Grandmother Goes to School for Paralytic Girl (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"At first, it was a little embarrassing for me to sit in the
classroom with teenagers, but gradually I got along with them very
well. They often helped me complete my notes during the break,"
Grandma said.
</P>
<P>
"Grandma" has become the nickname of Dong in the school. Not
only do her young classmates call her so, but also the teachers
and the principal.
</P>
<P>
"Grandma is always the first to arrive at school and her
notebook is often shown as a model in the class," one of the
teachers said.
</P>
<P>
The major subjects of the vocational high school are computer
skills, accounting and English. None of them is easy for an elderly
lady of 71 to learn.
</P>
<P>
"I would have no chances to learn new technology like computers
without the new schooling experience for Wang Li," Grandma said.
</P>
<P>
Several months ago, Wang Li had a big operation. With
the help of Grandma, she practised Chinese typing on a keyboard
in bed. Now she can write both English and Chinese articles on the
computer.
</P>
<P>
Wang Li has won several national awards for her strong will as
a handicapped child. But she owes all her achievements to Grandma.
</P>
<P>
Her favorite song is Mariah Carey's "Hero", which goes,"There's
a hero if you look inside your heart...and the sorrow that you
know will melt away." She said," Grandma is my heroine."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
