<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aged Grandmother Goes to School for Paralytic Girl (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- When the new semester began,
students in the Computer Vocational High School of Chongqing
in Southwest China was surprised to find a hoary-headed old woman
sitting with them in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
The 71-year-old woman is called Dong Shizhi, who has been
attending the school for her paralytic granddaughter in the past
seven years.
</P>
<P>
Every day, she takes notes in the classes, repeats the lessons
at home to her granddaughter, Wang Li, and then hands in the
girl's homework to the teachers the next day.
</P>
<P>
In this way, the 16-year-old girl has finished junior middle
school and received top scores in the entrance examination to a
vocational high school this year.
</P>
<P>
The age of 16 to a girl like Wang means youth, vigor and
happiness, but life is harsh to Wang Li. She was born with
congenital spinal bifida and has never been able to stand, let
alone walk.
</P>
<P>
"I carried her on my back to school before she was ten, but
then her condition worsened and she had to drop out of school,"
said Wang's father.
</P>
<P>
To comfort the girl, Grandma Dong, who graduated from a
university in the early 1950s, decided to build a bridge between
Wang Li and the school herself. At the age of 64, she appeared in
the primary school classroom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SI To Continue Dialogue With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BEIJING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Pierre Mauroy, visiting
chairman of Socialist International (SI), a world-wide
organization for parties advocating socialist democracy, has said
that SI is willing to continue its dialogue and co-operation with
the Communist Party of China (CPC).
</P>
<P>
Mauroy's current visit is the first by a SI chairman since
1984 when his predecessor, chancellor of the former Federal
Republic of Germany, Willy Brandt, visited China and reached an
agreement with the CPC to open up regular dialogues. Mauroy said
during a recent exclusive interview with Xinhua that his current
visit is aimed at discussions on issues of common interest and at
continuing cooperation with the CPC.
</P>
<P>
The SI and the CPC share common points and also have
divergences, and he came here this time for candid dialogues on
the basis of mutual respect,
 Mauroy said, adding that cooperation is beneficial to all parties.
</P>
<P>
The chairman has exchanged views with Chinese leaders on
ideology, the market economy, democracy, legislation, and other
issues during his stay in Beijing. He said he believes his talks
with president Jiang Zemin were very fruitful, expressing the
conviction that this meeting, which proceeded in a
 cordial atmosphere, were indicative of sound contacts and
dialogues in the future.
</P>
<P>
Mauroy visited China in 1985 as prime-minister of France and
mayor of Lille. China has witnessed dramatic changes during the
past 13 years, he said when recalling his former visit.
</P>
<P>
The SI, established in 1951 and headquartered in London, has
139 member parties. It advocates a market economy under
macro-control, supports North-South dialogue and cooperation, and
upholds disarmament and peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
