<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sand Dunes Eyed as Source of Wealth (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Decades ago, many farmers left
their homes in Yulin Prefecture in northwest China's Shaanxi
Province because of the invasion of sand dunes. Today, most of them
have come back as the dunes continue to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
Just as an American journalist wrote in a recent "Time"
magazine article, it is amazing to see how this place, a desert
land in the past, has turned into an area covered with green grass
and trees.
</P>
<P>
Many people agree that the people of Yulin have achieved much
in their desert-control efforts. Hundreds of foreign experts have
visited the area to discuss desert control methods during the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
A 1,500-kilometer-long forest belt now surrounds the moving
sand dunes, and most of the desert area has been covered with
poplar and willow trees as well as other plants; and on both
sides of the Wuding and Yixi rivers, high-yield paddy fields have
replaced barren beaches.
</P>
<P>
Yulin Prefecture, located at the southern border of the Muus
Desert, includes seven cities, counties and 95 townships in a
sandy area covering 24,400 square kilometers, more than 50 percent
of the prefecture's total area.
</P>
<P>
In earlier times, Yulin was a place with a developed agriculture
and animal husbandry. But over the centuries, continuous wars,
blind farming and the excessive felling of trees seriously damaged
the land and it eventually became a desert.
</P>
<P>
By 1949, the moving dunes had surmounted the Great Wall and
moved southward for more than 50 kilometers, burying tens of
thousands of hectares of arable land and pastures, six townships
and more than 400 villages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sand Dunes Eyed as Source of Wealth (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Li Junzhi, director of the Yulin Prefectural Forestry Bureau,
said that sand storms often hit the area just a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
He said the people of Yulin have made great efforts to fight
against desertification for generations. However, there were still
over 533,000 hectares of unimproved desert in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
Many farmers left their homes and settled down in other
places because of the threat of the desert.
</P>
<P>
This situation has changed greatly since the implementation of
reform and opening up to the outside world. A series of policies
adopted by the local government, under which people who plant
trees can make a profit of their own, has lured many farmers
back.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two decades, more than 10,000 rural families have
contracted for desert land to plant trees and have turned more than
333,000 hectares of desert into green land.
</P>
<P>
Some farmers have established desert control companies and
achieved the twin purposes of stopping the expansion of the desert
and and realizing good economic returns by developing irrigated
farmland and raising domestic animals.
</P>
<P>
Local officials said that this successful desert control should
also be attributed to technical guidance provided by experts and
support from China's Air Force which has conducted aerial
planting for years.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that by the end of 1997 Yulin had planted trees
on 793,000 hectares, with the forest coverage rate rising to 39.8
percent from the former 1.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the 1970s, annual sand storm days have dropped to
22 from 66, and the annual moving speed of the dunes has slowed to 1.6
meters from 7 meters. And the amount of soil and sand washed into
the Yellow River has dropped by 76 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
At present, the area has developed 6,667 hectares of grain land
with an output of 15,000 kilograms, and more than 6,666.7 hectares
of high-yield paddy land. In 1997, the per capita income for local
farmers reached 1,400 yuan (168.7 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Local people now regard the sand dunes as a source of wealth,
and some 10,000 farmers have moved into the sandy areas in the
past several years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Host World Congress of Architects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The 20th World Congress of
the International Union of Architects (UIA) is scheduled to be
held in Beijing on June 23, 1999, the first to be hosted in an
Asian country.
</P>
<P>
According to Yu Zhengsheng, chairman of the Chinese organizing
committee of the 20th UIA Congress and Chinese minister of
construction, the upcoming congress is expected to attract over
7,000 architectural experts and officials from more than 100
countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the congress is "Architecture in the 21st
Century". Under this theme, six sub-themes including "Architecture
and Environment," "Architecture and Urbanism," "Architecture and
Technology," "Architecture and Culture," "Architecture and
Professionism," and "Architectural Education and Young Architects"
will also be addressed.
</P>
<P>
Along with reports on special topics and nearly 100 meetings
for academic exchanges, the congress will launch a series of
activities under the title "Urban Housing for the 21st Century,"
including a student design competition, the main theme exhibition,
a UIA national section architecture exhibition, and a Chinese
architecture exhibition.
</P>
<P>
The congress will publish a "Collection of Congress Papers"
and a ten-volume work entitled "World Architecture: A Critical
Mosaic, 1900-2000."
</P>
<P>
This congress has won support from the Chinese government and
the municipal government of Beijing. The organizing committee,
composed of leading members from 16 chinese ministries and
commissions, has been set up with the approval of the State
Council.
</P>
<P>
Li Ruihuan, member of the Standing Committee of the Political
Bureau of the CPC Central Committee and Chairman of the national
committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC), will act as honorary chairman of the Chinese
organizing committee.
</P>
<P>
The International Union of Architects (UIA) was founded in
1948, and now has more than 100 member countries involving more
than one-million architects all over the world. The congress is
held every three years, and 19 have been staged since the founding
of the UIA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
