<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Henan Non-State Industries Enjoy Boom Cycle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Non-state industries,
espciallly collective and private ventures, are playing an
increasingly pivotal role in industrial development in central
China's Henan Province.
</P>
<P>
Collectives account for 30.7 percent of the local industrial
output value, with the private sector contributing an additional
28.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
State-owned businesses currently account for 27.6 percent of
the industrial output value and 51.3 percent of industrial capital.
</P>
<P>
Non-state enterprises employ over 70 percent of the industrial
production workforce, with state-owned enterprises employing 20.9
percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
The share-holding, foreign-funded and private sectors account
for a third of total industrial capital.
</P>
<P>
The province has 635,300 small industrial enterprises which
contribute more than 75 percent of industrial pretax profits.
</P>
<P>
Traditional industries, including the coal, metallurgical,
building materials, foodstuffs, textile, chemicals, machinery and
power generation sectors, continue to be a major factor in local
industrial development.
</P>
<P>
Some 70 percent of capital in industrial enterprises at and
above the county level involves traditional industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Violent Turmoil Ebbs, But Tension Persists in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Violent turmoil in Tirana is
apparently on the ebb after it shook the Albanians and even the
world in the past few days, but tension persists and threatens to
reach far into the future.
</P>
<P>
The swirl of violence was touched off by the assassination last
Saturday of Azem Hajdari, a leading opposition deputy in
parliament and one of the founders of the Democratic Party (DP)
led by former president Sali Berisha.
</P>
<P>
The DP reacted with immediate and fierce lashes at the
government as Berisha accused Socialist Prime Minister Fatos Nano
of masterminding the murder and police agents of pulling the
trigger.
</P>
<P>
Berisha's speech incited hundreds of DP members and supporters
to armed attacks the next day on the Public Security Ministry and
the Prime Minister's Office.
</P>
<P>
They opened fire at the buildings, burnt several offices on the
first floor and left nothing intact in nearby parking lots.
</P>
<P>
The unrest grew more bloody on Monday morning when Hajdari's
funeral procession escalated into an armed riot involving
thousands of supporters of Berisha who shot or threw grenades at
the Prime Minister's Office building.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses reported deafening roars of gun fires and billows of
smoke filling the air throughout the street.
</P>
<P>
In the following hours, protesters seized five tanks from the
army, occupied several state institutions including the
parliament, the government building, the constitutional court and
the Finance Ministry and wreaked havoc in places they passed.
</P>
<P>
They broadcast Berisha's speech at the state radio and
television and announced their full control of the capital.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 12 opposition parties led by the DP issued an
ultimatum to the government demanding Nano's resignation within 24
hours and establishment of a technical cabinet to prepare new
elections.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties also sent representatives for talks with
President Rexhep Mejdani.
</P>
<P>
However, events did not take their expected course as police
and special army units intervened in the afternoon, arresting some
of the rioters and seized many weapons.
</P>
<P>
By early evening, the police had brought under control an
"armed coup d'etat", as was charged by the parliament and
government.
</P>
<P>
At least three people were killed and dozens injured in the
clashes which also caused unestimatable economic losses, according
to the Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Late Tuesday evening, Nano said at a cabinet meeting that "the
state will not protect the lives of criminals" and "the security
forces will strike out at crimes without mercy."
</P>
<P>
While affirming the determination to punish murderers of
Hajdari, the Albanian government ordered the DP to hand over
hidden weapons and announced it would prosecute all those involved
in the coup attempt.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the parliament called for early government
efforts to restore social order and normal lives of citizens.
</P>
<P>
At the request of the state prosecutor, a parliamentary
commission met on Wednesday to consider stripping Berisha of his
parliamentary immunity along with five other DP officials and
leaving them open to investigations under law.
</P>
<P>
DP leaders are continuing to defend their roles in the Monday
riot, rejecting accusations of a coup attempt and insisting on
Nano's resignation.
</P>
<P>
In defiance of a police ban, the opposition staged what they
called "peaceful demonstrations" in Tirana on Tuesday and
Wednesday, which passed off without incidents.
</P>
<P>
Although the turbulence in Albania has started to show signs of
easing, analysts warned that the ensuing political conflict would
die hard and its aftermath would have deep-going impact on the
country's future developments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
