<HEADLINE> Beijing Restricts Itinerant Population </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Beijing, the Chinese capital,
plans to strengthen the management of some two million itinerant
workers, according to reports presented in Tuesday's fifth meeting
of the Standing Committee of the 11th Beijing Municipal People's
Congress.
</P>
<P>
Li Quanfu, director of the itinerant population management
program, said that 2.86 million itinerant workers account for
almost 20 percent of the capital's total population.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that the large influx of itinerant workers has
promoted the development of various sectors, but has also created
problems in terms of sanitation and security.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Public Security Bureau has instituted strong
measures to combat crimes committed by itinerants. Law enforcement
departments had arrested some 3,600 itinerants for alleged
involvement in criminal acts by the end of July this year, with
the figure accounting for 56.6 percent of the total number of the
suspects detained.
</P>
<P>
The new regulation restricts the number of itinerants working
in the industrial and commercial sectors and will limit the total
related workers in the city to 1.81 million by year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government has pledged to provide better services
and protection for itinerant workers. The city also plans to
establish a professional training center for the itinerant
population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
