<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leeches May Hold Cure for Rheumatoid Arthritis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Leeches could hold clues
for
the treatment of rheumatoid arthritis.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand Press Association (NZPA) reported Thursday that
a
team composed of scientists at Auckland University's School of
Biology has discovered that a chemical found in European leeches
may
slow the growth of cells in joints affected by rheumatoid
arthritis.
</P>
<P>
The team hopes its research can tell them how the leech-based
chemical reduces arthritis so it can be turned into a drug to beat

the crippling condition.
</P>
<P>
The European leech has long been used for its medical
properties
and more recently for treating people whose limbs have been
severed
or crushed.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to anti-coagulants in its saliva, the European leech has

also been found to benefit heart patients by reducing the risk of

blood clots.
</P>
<P>
Doctors here have already been using a New Zealand leech
variety
to restore blood flow to severed limbs.
</P>
<P>
The NZPA quoted Auckland University biochemist Ken Scott as
saying he is now examining the Kiwi variety to establish whether
it
has healing properties similar to its European cousin.
</P>
<P>
Scott has been awarded a grant by the Auckland Medical Research

Foundation to carry out the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
