<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Joins EU Flight Ban Against Belgrade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Britain has joined a
European Union (EU) ban on flights by the Yugoslav carrier to the
union member states, according to European Commission sources.
</P>
<P>
Britain had said that it could not implement the ban in that it
has to give a year's notice to the Yugoslav national carrier JAT
due to a 1959 bilateral aviation agreement.
</P>
<P>
But the British move annoyed its EU partners.
</P>
<P>
The ban, first agreed upon unanimously in June and finalized
earlier this month, went into effect on September 8.
</P>
<P>
Now only one of the 15 EU member states, Greece, still has not
decided how to move. Greece cited the same excuse as Britain's for
not applying the flight ban.
</P>
<P>
European Commission President Jacques Santer said earlier that
a decision made by the 15 (member states) should be implemented by
the 15 and the commission president saw the incident of
non-implementation as a failure on the part of the union.
</P>
<P>
Britain told the weekly commission meeting Wednesday that it
was changing position after British Prime Minister Tony Blair
called Santer to indicate that his country was on the point of
changing position.
</P>
<P>
The commission meeting, held at Strasbourg, was scheduled to
discuss the possibility of taking Britain and Greece to the
European Court of Justice over their non-application of the EU
decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
