<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Debt Removal Key to Africa's Growth: UNCTAD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 17 (Xinhua) -- A rapid removal of the
current debt burden is vital for Africa's long-term economic
growth, a latest report from a United Nations agency said.
</P>
<P>
Africa's external debt is the highest in the developing
region, said the 1998 report of the U.N. Conference on Trade and
Development (UNCTAD).
</P>
<P>
"There is now ample evidence that Africa's external debt
burden is having a severe adverse impact on investment and
renewed growth," the Daily Nation Thursday quoted UNCTAD chief
Rubens Ricupero as saying in the report.
</P>
<P>
External debt has impeded public investment in physical and
human infrastructure, as well as growth-enhancing spending on
health and education.
</P>
<P>
Ricupero noted that the extent of the debt is indicated by
accumulated arrears which, by 1996, reached more than 64 billion
U.S. Dollars, amounting to more than a quarter of the total debt
in the whole of Africa.
</P>
<P>
Of the greatest concern, according to Ricupero, is that
"two-thirds of the increase in debt since 1988 has been due to
arrears."
</P>
<P>
The debt burden has created a problem of policy credibility
and uncertainty for Africa's private investors whose gains from
investments could be taxed away to service debts, said the UNCTAD
report.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Africa has much growth potential "but
it needs fresh policies, institutional reforms and a swift
solution to the debt problem if it is to fully exploit this
potential."
</P>
<P>
The report warns that there would be no growth in Africa
unless appropriate domestic policies is put in place to overcome low
productivity and heavy dependence on a small number of
commodities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Company Builds Polder in Hangzhou Bay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 16 (Xinhua) --A Shanghai company will use
silt deposited in the Yangtze River estuary to build a polder in
the Luchaogang area near suburban Nanhui county on the shores of
Hangzhou Bay.
</P>
<P>
Li Tanglong, general manager of the Shanghai Polder
Construction and Development Co. Ltd, said the company has
invested 50 million yuan to construct a 4.5-km diversion dike to
promote silting in 300 sq.km. tidal area east of Nanhui.
</P>
<P>
Li said the company will invest another 50 million yuan to
extend the dike by an additional six km. during second phase
construction. The project will create over 3,533 ha of
cultivatable land by the year 2,000, according to Li.
</P>
<P>
The polder will also provide land to support construction of
deepwater port facilities at Dayangshan and Xiaoyangshan which are
located in the eastern section of Hangzhou Bay. The polder will
offer ideal conditions for building auxiliary port facilities,
according to said experts.
</P>
<P>
They added that the planned polder will not only provide
Shanghai with reserve land for developing agriculture, animal
husbandry and fisheries, and will in turn promote economic
growth. Experts estimate the cost for developing one hectare of
cultivatable land will approach 300,000 yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
