<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Post-flood Rehabilitation Underway in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's two ministries are
starting the work of post-flood rehabilitation, press reports here
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Repair and reconstruction of the roads damaged by the deluge
will cost the government about 13.7 billion taka (291.5 million
U.S. dollars), The Daily Star quoted officials of the
Communications Ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
The cost has been estimated on the basis of damage caused by
the floods up to September 15, they added.
</P>
<P>
"The donor agencies have already been approached for necessary
funds for the repair work," they said, adding that the funding
organizations had already responded positively.
</P>
<P>
The ministry would soon finalize the issue of disbursement of
necessary funds for immediate repair of the roads, they disclosed.
</P>
<P>
About 3,800 kilometers of various roads have been badly damaged
while 4,000 kilometers have been partially damaged during the
over-two-month-long floods this year.
</P>
<P>
The ministry estimated that 35 percent of the roads in the
country including national and regional highways as well as feeder
roads have been affected by the deluge, with the total length at
2,862, 1,564 and 15,858 kilometers respectively and 546 culverts
and 562 bridges damaged or washed away.
</P>
<P>
The Food and Agriculture Ministry has taken adequate measures
to recover the losses in the agricultural sector caused by the
devastating floods, the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Considering the commitments and responses from the donors, the
government's massive post-flood rehabilitation program and courage
and fortitude of the people in facing the calamity, Agricultural
Minister Begum Motia Chowdhurry said Wednesday, "We are sure to
overcome the crisis."
</P>
<P>
The government has already decided to launch a massive
post-flood agricultural rehabilitation program under which 32.7
billion taka (695.7 million dollars) agricultural loan would be
provided for the flood-affected farmers on easy terms, she stated.
</P>
<P>
According to the preliminary estimates by the ministry, the
floods have damaged 562,950 hectares of crops causing a shortage
of at least two million tons of grains.
</P>
<P>
The government would also try to distribute vegetable, wheat
and maize seeds free of cost among the poor and marginal farmers,
she said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the government had taken some administrative measures
to help rehabilitate the farmers, and it had already withdrawn the
duty on the import of farm tools, she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
