<HEADLINE> E-Business Manifests More Importance in Chinese Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese businesses,
especially small- and medium-sized enterprises, should readily
accept rather than treat electronic business as a new concept.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Department of Small- and Medium-Sized
Enterprises under China's Economic and Trade Commission voiced the
assertion during today's solutions fair jointly organized by the
commission and Intel Corporation. He said the major challenge for
Chinese companies is how to gear their management systems to
computer and networking technology.
</P>
<P>
Wee Theng Tan, chief operations officer and managing director
of Intel (China), said the company, the world's largest chip
manufacturer, will offer state-of-the-art networking technology to
fulfill the needs of Chinese businesses.
</P>
<P>
"The sales volume for the global electronic business will hit
200 billion US dollars by the end of the century," said Wee,
adding that "upgrading information technology is not simply a
luxury, but instead a demand of business competition."
</P>
<P>
The fair featured two seminars in which entrepreneurs and
engineers introduced their experiences in using information and
networking technology.
</P>
<P>
Jimmy Wang, president of Hong Kong-based China Infobank Ltd.,
said networking "places small companies on the same footing with
larger companies in terms of the use of information resources."
</P>
<P>
A senior commission official told participants in a recent
conference on policies regarding the introduction of foreign
investment policies that will seek more foreign funds to
accelerate an information revolution in its enterprise sector.
</P>
<P>
Intel has sponsored seminars in a number of Chinese cities,
including Shanghai, Guangzhou and Chengdu.
</P>
<P>
Various other multinationals, including IBM and Microsoft, have
also launched plans to expand cooperation with small businesses.
</P>
<P>
The number of online companies and individuals is expected to
grow from 1.17 million to over seven million over the next few
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
