<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, September 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Dry weather conditions are likely to cut deep,
probably by over one-third, into the year's maize harvest in the
Yugoslav federation.
</P>
<P>
The official Tanjug news agency said the country's total maize
output this year, by estimation, would be 5.55 million metric
tons, down three million tons from last year. (Yugoslavia-Maize
Output)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Britain's unemployment has continued to fall despite
the recent spate of high profile redundancy announcements.
</P>
<P>
Government figures show that in the three months to July the
main measure of unemployment dropped by 55,000 to 1,790,000, a
jobless rate of 6.2 percent. The older measure of unemployment,
which counts the number of people out of work and claiming
benefits, fell by 16,400 in August to 1.3 million, the lowest
level since May 1980. (UK-Unemployment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The Russian ruble tumbled again Wednesday, with the
Central Bank's official rate shedding 22.8 percent amid fears of
rising inflation.
</P>
<P>
The official rate, based on the average of trading on the
Moscow Interbank Currency Exchange (MICEX), fell to 12.45 to the
dollar from 9.6 to the dollar the day before. (Russia-Ruble-Dive)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
