<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water-Borne Diseases Likely to Attack 20 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- At least 20 million people are
feared to be attacked by water-borne diseases such as diarrhea
after the recession of waters in flood-hit areas in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
This was stated by the Ministry of Health and Family Welfare in
a primary estimate, the Bangladesh Observer daily reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Health officials are now apprehending an outbreak of epidemics
in the flood-affected areas if necessary measures are not taken on
emergency basis to prevent the proliferation of the water-borne
diseases in the post-flood period, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
About 60 to 70 percent of the flood victims may face serious
health hazards including diarrheal diseases, fungal, malaria,
scabies, jaundice, acute respiratory track infection and
pneumonia, a medical university associate professor said.
</P>
<P>
The death toll from diarrhea has so far risen to 195 while the
number of affected people has reached over 229,000, according to
the Health Department Control Room.
</P>
<P>
Some 2,108 doctors have been working with 4,409 medical teams
across the country to provide medical services to the flood
victims, official sources said.
</P>
<P>
Nearly three-fourths of the country and about two-thirds of the
capital city Dhaka were under water at a certain period during the
over-two-month-long floods, directly and indirectly affecting
about half of the country's 127 million people, with about 30
million seriously hit in 52 of the 64 districts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
