<HEADLINE> Pakistani FM Leaves for Tehran for Talks on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Satarj Aziz Thursday morning left for Tehran on a special visit to
promote conciliation and avert the dangers of a military
confrontation between Iran and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan is deeply concerned about the heightening of tension
between Iran and Afghanistan which could pose a serious threat to
the peace and security in the region, said a press release issued
by the Foreign Ministry Wednesday announcing Aziz's visit to Iran.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan hoped that Iran and the Taliban regime will resolve
their difference through peaceful negotiations and Pakistan will
continue to cooperate closely with the two countries to defuse the
present crisis, the release said.
</P>
<P>
Aziz will be carrying a letter from Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
for Iranian President Mohammad Khatami. He will assure the Iranian
leadership of Pakistan's commitment to the abiding friendship
between Pakistan and Iran which transcends all vicissitudes.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister will also emphasize the allegation of
Pakistan's interference in Afghanistan was "a fabrication of the
enemies of Pakistan and Iran friendship."
</P>
<P>
Tension between Iran and the Taliban has been arising following
the killing of nine Iranian diplomats by the hard-line militia in
its capture of the northern Afghan city Mazar-e-Sharif early last
month. Iran has vowed to take revenge by any means and already
deployed about 200,000 troops along the Afghan border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
