<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania Streamlining Foreign Ministry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Romanian Foreign
Ministry decided Wednesday to streamline its organization in a bid
to join the North Atlantic Treaty Organization and the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
To make full use of its limited manpower and money, Foreign
Minister Andrei Plesu announced that the ministry will cut the
number of state secretary posts from four to two, and close its
embassies in the Congo, Ethiopia, Guinea, Mozambique, Namibia and
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
To demonstrate its determination to help resolve the Kosovo
crisis, the ministry has decided to increase the number of
Romanian diplomats in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also decided to open embassies in Armenia and
Azerbaijan in a hope to further strengthen its diplomatic
activities in the Caucasus and make sure it will continue to
receive its much-needed petroleum and natural gas from the region.
</P>
<P>
In a sluggish economy and with limited funds, how to
concentrate manpower and money on priorities is a major problem
for the foreign ministry.
</P>
<P>
Creating favorable conditions for joining NATO and the EU and
developing friendly relations with neighboring countries are
important elements in Romania's foreign policies that cry out for
structural reform within the ministry, experts say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
