<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sweden, U.S. Join Hands to Fight Organized Crimes, Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Swedish authorities
will step up cooperation with the U.S. Federal Bureau of
Investigation (FBI) to clamp down organized crimes and
international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Swedish journalists on Wednesday, FBI Director
Louis Freeh said that the first step of bilateral cooperation will
be information sharing and criminals chasing.
</P>
<P>
The major target will be crimes originated in Russia and other
East European countries, including money laundering, drug
trafficking, gambling and blackmail.
</P>
<P>
Organized crimes usually expand across countries, Freeh said,
international cooperation is thus needed to fight them.
</P>
<P>
He said the FBI has rich information on organized crimes in the
Baltic region, which the FBI hopes to share with other nations.
</P>
<P>
The director noted that terrorists are possible to act anywhere
any time, as proved by the embassy bombings in Kenya and Tanzania
a month ago. But he did not mention whether Sweden is threatened.
</P>
<P>
Freeh arrived here on Wednesday and has met Swedish Minister
of Justice Laila Freivalds, Junior Minister of Foreign Affairs
Pierre Schori and other officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
