<HEADLINE> Thai Government Hit by Corruption Scandal: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's coalition
government has seen its approval rating falling by 10 percent
because of a corruption scandal involving the Health Ministry.
</P>
<P>
An Assumption University poll, published by the Nation
newspaper Thursday, showed that the approval rate of the
government's performance dropped to 45.6 percent after the
revelations of the scandal. The rate was 56 percent in August.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,200 people in Bangkok and the suburbs took part in
the survey on Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Rakkiat Sukthana submitted his resignation
Tuesday after his ministry was accused of purchasing and
re-selling over-priced drugs to companies.
</P>
<P>
Of the people polled, 66.2 percent agreed that Rakkiat should
resign and 14.8 percent disagreed while 19 percent declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
Some 60.4 percent said Rakkiat should be given a chance to
resume his post should the panel investigating the scandal find
that he was not involved in the case while 26.2 percent said he
should not have the chance and 13.4 percent declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
About 48.7 percent said Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai should
reshuffle the cabinet, 7.1 percent said Chuan himself should
resign, 6 percent said he should dissolve the parliament and 9
percent refused to comment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
