<HEADLINE> U.S. Approves 2 Billion Dollar Weapons Sale to Emirates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Defense
Department said on Wednesday that it has approved a sale of two
billion U.S. dollars worth of weapons to the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
The UAE decided earlier this year to buy 80 American-made F-16
jet aircraft.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the Pentagon said the sale involves material to
support the aircraft purchase and includes missiles, bombs and a
variety of support equipment and training.
</P>
<P>
"The proposed sale of the weapons and munitions will strengthen
the UAE as a potential coalition partner, reducing the dependence
on U.S. forces in the region while enhancing any coalition
operations the U.S. undertakes," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The prime contractor is Raytheon of Lexington, Massachusetts,
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
In separate statements, the Pentagon also announced it has
approved potential sales of 112 Standard missiles to Spain at a
cost of 105 million U.S. dollars, 24 Standard missiles worth 24
million U.S. dollars to the Netherlands and six CH-47C Chinook
helicopters to Egypt at a cost of 203 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
