<HEADLINE> 680,000 Thai School Children Have Eyesight Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Some 680,000 primary school
children have been found to be suffering from eyesight problems,
the Bangkok Post said Thursday, quoting the Office of Primary
Education Commission (OPEC).
</P>
<P>
The office has decided to make eyesight tests obligatory for
primary school children.
</P>
<P>
Kasama Voravan na Ayudhya, the OPEC's secretary-general, said
she has ordered all primary education offices to conduct basic
eyesight checks on school children and provide them with
spectacles if needed.
</P>
<P>
OPEC's move came after an initial survey by a hospital's
Eye-glasses Bank, which found some 680,000 children, or about 10
percent, at primary schools nationwide have eyesight or other
visual problems.
</P>
<P>
Most of those who have eye problems are suffering from
short-sightedness or myopia, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
A coordinator at the Eye-glasses Bank said visual problems in
these children have worsened due to lack of care from parents and
teachers, as well as lack of proper treatment.
</P>
<P>
She said that unless these problems are detected and treated at
an early stage, they will be impossible to correct.
</P>
<P>
Visual impairment directly affects children's learning ability.
Children with eyesight problems, especial myopia, usually develop
headaches when they try to focus their eyes, and in some cases
they simply give up their studies, she said.
</P>
<P>
The coordinator suggested that teachers be trained to perform
basic eyesight tests so that eye problems in children can be
detected early and corrected properly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
