<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Launches Campaign Against German Measles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has launched a
national immunization campaign to eliminate German measles,
according to Health Ministry sources Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The sources quoted Minister of Health Nimal Siripala de Silva
as saying at a seminar Wednesday that German measles had earlier
contributed to the birth of disabled children causing pain of mind
and depression to parents and families.
</P>
<P>
The campaign named "Rubella Immunization Program", will
initially cover the female population of 3.1 million in the 11 to
44 age group in Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Already 4 million doses of Rubella vaccine costing 90,000 U.S.
dollars had been imported by the government.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that around 900 disabled children are born each
year in Sri Lanka. The immunization project is expected to reduce
the number considerably.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that the danger of German measles is that its
 symptoms are so light that many who are affected do not know that
they have the disease, and that the best way to tackle the problem
is immunization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
