<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian PM: Albanian Situation Returning to Normal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Rome, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano
Prodi voiced satisfaction Wednesday that the Albanian situation
appeared to be returning to normal.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in parliament, Prodi admitted that "for a while" he
feared the repetition of last year's anarchy that spurred Italy to
lead an international mission to restore order and pave the way
for elections.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said he was in constant touch with Albanian leaders,
urging them to end the violence and resume political talks.
</P>
<P>
He said Italy and the international community were entitled to
make such calls because of their action in bolstering Albania's
fledgling democracy and aiding its economic and civic
reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
In Tirana, opposition leader and ex-president Sali Berisha was
acclaimed by thousands of supporters in another peaceful
demonstration Wednesday in the main Skanderbeg Square.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference later, Berisha rejected suggestions that
Monday's disturbances had been a coup attempt. He said they were
the result of a "trap" laid by Socialist Prime Minister Fatos Nano.
</P>
<P>
The European Union Wednesday named Austrian diplomat Herbert
Grebmayr as its special envoy to Albania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
