<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central America Tourism Revenues Expected to Grow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Central America's tourism
revenues are expected to be up 14 percent this year from the 1.7
billion U.S. dollars reaped last year, said a regional trade group.
</P>
<P>
In a report released here on Wednesday, the Central America
Tourism Integration System (CATIS) put the number of people
visiting countries in the region at about 2.8 million a year.
</P>
<P>
By countries, tourist visits to Nicaragua increased the most
quickly by 21 percent in 1997 compared with 10 years ago, to Costa
Rica, up by 11 percent, and El Salvador, by 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
As for the tourism income, the report said, Nicaragua
registered a 21.9 percent growth over that of 10 years ago, Costa
Rica 11 percent, and El Salvador 13.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Nicaragua is the most frequently visited country, because
citizens from other countries such as Guatemala, El Salvador and
Honduras do not need a passport to travel within the region,
instead they only use an identification (ID) card.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica is not part of this ID agreement, so it is the least
country, said the CATIS report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's GDP Up By 5.1 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's gross domestic
product (GDP) grew by 5.1 percent during the first half of this
year, the Central Bank said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The GDP in real terms went up by 4.4 percent during the second
quarter of 1998 in contrast to the 5.8-percent growth in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
During the second quarter of the year, bank sources said, the
services sector accounted for 51 percent of the overall growth
while the manufacturing sector grew by 25.6 percent, construction
13.8 percent and the agricultural, forestry and fishing sector 4.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
The transport services and communication sub-sector increased
by 37 percent. The factory industry which accounts for 80 percent
of the manufacturing industry grew by 8.1 percent. The impetus was
mainly from the textile and wearing apparel industry which
achieved a 10.9-percent growth.
</P>
<P>
The food and beverages sector also grew by 4.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
External trade in July recorded a surplus of 9 million U.S.
dollars, with exports standing at 511 million dollars and imports
502 million dollars, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
The bank earlier said Sri Lanka's economic growth in terms of
GDP was expected to be in the range of 5 to 5.5 percent this year.
Sri Lanka enjoyed a growth of 6.4 percent last year from 3.8
percent in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
