<HEADLINE> Mexico Rejects U.S. Nuclear Waste Dumping in Border Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Mexico will continue to
negotiate with the United States on relocating U.S. nuclear waste,
a top Mexican environment official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Julia Carabias, secretary of the Department of Environment,
Natural Resources and Fishing, called for changing the U.S. plan
to dump hazardous waste near the area bordering on Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Senate recently authorized the states of Vermont and
Maine to send low-radiation nuclear waste to a new dump in Sierra
Blanca, Texas, 25 kilometers away from the border with Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Carabias said the Mexican government has refused such dump in
border areas several times, and has sent representatives to the
United States to discuss and study the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
