<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Key Ally of Italian Government Unhappy with Budget Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government's left
ally, the Communist Refoundation, said Wednesday it was "very
worried" about plans for the 1999 budget, raising the prospect of
an imminent break with Prime Minister Romano Prodi.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting in which Prodi outlined the new budget bill to
party leaders from his parliamentary majority, the Communist
Refoundation Secretary Fausto Bertinotti said it failed to meet
his calls for a drastic shift in policy.
</P>
<P>
"The change isn't there," said Bertinotti, who has been
demanding for months that this year's budget do more to promote
jobs and support the unemployed.
</P>
<P>
He has made it plain that if the budget fails to satisfy
demands he will withdraw his party's support and bring the
government down.
</P>
<P>
The scenario is a repeat of last autumn when, in return for its
continued support, the party forced Prodi to concede a commitment
on a 35-hour week and the creation of a southern jobs agency.
</P>
<P>
Referring to budget plans he had been shown Wednesday night,
Bertinotti said that at times there seemed to be an attempt to
meet his demands, but then it became clear that "substance was
lacking.
</P>
<P>
"When it comes to the actual spending, there's always money for
supporting business, but if its for pensioners or for the
unemployed, then it becomes very tight," he said.
</P>
<P>
Bertinotti noted that the meeting was the first of several and
hence there was still time for an agreement to be reached.
</P>
<P>
Franco Marini, leader of the People's Party, said there would
be another meeting next week, but that Wednesday's meeting had
gone "rather well."
</P>
<P>
Massimo D'Alema, head of the biggest party in the ruling Olive
Tree coalition, downplayed the difference between the Communist
Refoundation and other parties in the government's majority.
</P>
<P>
"The differences aren't such as to imply a break," he said.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema noted that there were several elements in Prodi's
package that should appeal to the Communist Refoundation. He
pointed in particular to the extra 5.5 trillion lire (3.24 billion
U.S. dollars) set aside to promote employment.
</P>
<P>
After explaining the budget to political leaders, Prodi met
with the employers' association Confindustria, which is also being
consulted on the package. He is expected to meet labor unions for
the same purpose on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
