<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yarlung Zangbo River Faces Increasing Danger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Experts warned today that the
Yarlung Zangbo River, which sits at the highest elevation of any
river in the world, faces the threat of becoming a seasonal or
inland river.
</P>
<P>
"Environmental conditions in the upper reaches of the river
continue to deteriorate, with glaciers withdrawing and both
tributaries and lakes going dry," said Yang Yong, a geologist and
member of a team exploring the river valley.
</P>
<P>
The Yarlung Zangbo finds its source on the Qinghai-Tibet
Plateau and empties into the Indian Ocean after passing through
India and Bangladesh. The river has long been a popular attraction
for explorers and adventurers from around the world.
</P>
<P>
Yang's 21-member team is undertaking a rafting expedition to
collect ecological data about the region. The mission was delayed
several weeks ago due to inclement weather in Tibet, but was
resumed earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Yang reported that the team arrived at the source of the river
last week and found that many wild species have either faced
extinction or have otherwise moved to other areas because of the
lack of water and dry climate.
</P>
<P>
Zhongba County, the county closest to the river's source, its
seat has been relocated three times due to desertification. The
existing county seat, established in 1996, will quite likely have
to be relocated again in 20 years, according to Puchong, secretary
of the Zhongba county Communist Party Committee.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot exclude the possibility that the river will become
either a seasonal or inland river if the current trend continues,"
said Yang.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a telephone interview with Xinhua News Agency, Yang
attributed the dangerous situation to global climate changes,
including the greenhouse effect and human activities depleting
forest resources.
</P>
<P>
He suggested the immediate implementation of an afforestation
project to hold back the encroaching desert and improve the
ecology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Participation Welcomes in Enterprise Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing municipal
government recently adopted 10 measures to encourage foreign
ventures to participate in the reform of the city's state-owned
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations, announced by the Beijing Municipal
Administration for Industry and Commerce, stipulate that foreign
ventures will be permitted to purchase or merge with state-owned
enterprises on a limited basis.
</P>
<P>
The regulations also allow foreign-funded ventures to jointly
establish ventures in the service sector.
</P>
<P>
Beijing welcomes Sino-foreign funded ventures to use technology
transfers to obtain shares in state-owned ventures. Technology
transfers can account for as much as 35 percent of total
registered funds in specified ventures, up substantially from the
former 20 percent ceiling.
</P>
<P>
The regulations grant the world's Top 500 ventures priority in
terms of participation in state-owned enterprises reform.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
