<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dry Weather Downing Yugoslavia's Maize Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Dry weather conditions are
likely to cut deep, probably by over one-third, into the year's
maize harvest in the Yugoslav federation.
</P>
<P>
The official Tanjug news agency said the country's total maize
output this year, by estimation, would be 5.55 million metric
tons, down three million tons from last year.
</P>
<P>
However, experts said the country, with a surplus of 1.5
million tons from last year, still has the ability to export one
million tons of maize after meeting the domestic needs.
</P>
<P>
In the same report, Tanjug said the output of sunflower seeds
and soybean is expected to reach 328,000 tons and 160,000 tons
respectively this year, more than enough for the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
As a result, said the report, the country would be able to
export 10,000 tons of cooking oil made from the two crops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
