<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania Joins EU in Sanctioning Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Romania has decided to join
the European Union countries in placing sanctions on the Yugoslav
Federation and banning Yugoslav airlines from landing in its
airports, the Foreign Ministry announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The move is a clear political signal to the Yugoslav
authorities, a statement by the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The statement strongly condemned the escalation of fighting in
the Serbian province of Kosovo, and extended a hope that Yugoslav
leaders would seek a peaceful solution through dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Romania, as a liaison country of the EU, will focus on
coordinating its foreign policy and security standards with those
of the EU, the statement noted.
</P>
<P>
Ten days ago, an EU foreign ministers' meeting in Austria made
the decision to ban Yugoslav airlines from landing in EU
countries, as part of a series of sanctions against the Yugoslav
Federation.
</P>
<P>
As a result, almost half of Yugoslav air routes have been
forced to close. 
</P>
</TEXT>
