<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0010 GMT September 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI -- Despite several natural disasters, Vietnam's farmers
are expecting a 31.3-million-ton harvest this year, including 28.4
million tons of rice, marking the fourth straight year of bumper
rice crops.
</P>
<P>
According to the General Statistics Department, this year's
rice output is the largest on record, 900,000 tons more than last
year. (Vietnam-Harvest)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The European Commission said Wednesday that Italy's
air traffic distribution plan between the two airports near Milan
violates European Union (EU) law.
</P>
<P>
European Transport Commissioner Neil Kinnock said that the
commission, the executive arm of the 15-nation EU, agreed that the
redistribution of air traffic between Linate and Malpensa airports
went against EU laws on fair competition.
</P>
<P>
The decision was originally postponed for a week so the Italian
government could reconsider its decree on moving almost all other
European countries' airlines out of the convenient Linate airport
to newly-built Malpensa. (Italy-Airport-EU)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
STOCKHOLM -- Swedish inflation fell by 0.5 percent in August,
bringing the annual inflation rate to about zero, down from nearly
two percent at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The August decline, which was mainly caused by a dramatic cut
in tobacco tax, was the largest in a single month since November
1992. (Sweden-Inflation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton and Czech President
Vaclav Havel met at the White House Wednesday to discuss European
security issues.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming Havel at a South Lawn ceremony by the White House,
Clinton praised the Czech president for his role in his country's
democratic process.
</P>
<P>
"It owes a very great deal, in our time, to the inspiration
provided by a single man, Vaclav Havel, who for years spoke when
it mattered and often at enormous personal cost," Clinton said.
(US-Czech-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KIEV -- The number of jobless in Ukraine reached 1.2 million by
the end of August, which accounting for 3.08 percent of the
workforce, the Interfax news agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate in the first eight months of 1998
increased by 50 percent over the same period of last year. The
rate in some states has reached five or six percent.
</P>
<P>
So far, 875,000 Ukrainians have registered as unemployed, but
with only 47,000 job vacancies, an average 18 jobless people will
compete for each post. (Ukraine-Unemployment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The "Gulf War syndrome" are not only common among
Gulf War veterans, they are also frequently reported by soldiers
who never went to the region, according to a new study.
</P>
<P>
The syndrome, such as fatigue, moodiness, memory problems and
muscle pain, that many Gulf War veterans complain of are not
likely to be explained by toxic exposures, exotic infections or
other risk factors peculiar to the war, said a report by a team of
epidemiologists in Wednesday's Journal of the American Medical
Association. (US-Gulf-War-Illness) 
</P>
</TEXT>
