<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Champions League Openers Witness Dramatic Finale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The opening matches of the
European Champions' League were added with the flavour of
dramatic finale with four games having their results changed in
the dying seconds.
</P>
<P>
Sinica Gogic of Olympiakos scored in the last minute to snatch
a 2-2 draw at Portuguese side Porto when the Greeks had trailed
2-0 with four minutes to go.
</P>
<P>
Brondby's Allan Ravn scored in the final minute to give his
Danish side a 2-1 victory over Bayern Munich, who had led 1-0
with three minutes left.
</P>
<P>
PSV Eindhoven's Arnold Bruggink was the hero to score in the
dying seconds to earn a 2-1 fightback win at home to HJK Helsinki.
</P>
<P>
And Lens striker Tony Vairelles, who won his first French cap
against Austria last month, earned a 1-1 draw against England's
Arsenal as the referee was about to blow his whistle.
</P>
<P>
Dutch Clarence Seedorf also hit a last minute goal for Real
Madrid who won 2-0 against Inter Milan, but the competition's
holders were set for victory anyway with Fernando Hierro
converting an 80th minute penalty.
</P>
<P>
And goals were flying in during the evening with 32 in the 12
matches.
</P>
<P>
Manchester United and Barcelona served up a feast of football
at Old Trafford as United threw away a 2-0 lead to draw 3-3.
</P>
<P>
Welsh wizard Ryan Giggs gave United a dream start by netting
after 17 minutes from a David Beckham cross from the right.
</P>
<P>
But once Giggs had opened the scoring it looked as if that
would open the floodgates and when Paul Scholes scored the second
on 24 minutes after Ruud Hesp had saved Dwight Yorke's overhead
kick that appeared to confirm that a runaway victory was on the
cards.
</P>
<P>
But after half-time it all started to go wrong for United,
with referee Stefano Braschi in their eyes the villain of the
piece.
</P>
<P>
First of all Sonny Anderson pulled one back with a neat finish
on 47 minutes.
</P>
<P>
And then the Italian official awarded Barcelona two penalties
in the second period -- the first of which was questionable --
with Giovanni and Luis Enrique finding the net.
</P>
<P>
Braschi sent off Nicky Butt for handling the ball for the
second spotkick.
</P>
<P>
Vairelles celebrated his recent arrival on the international
scene by stealing a point with an last-gasp header for Lens to
deny Arsenal.
</P>
<P>
All looked lost for the French until Vairelles, who made his de
but for France a month ago, nodded home from close range
following a Daniel Moreira left-wing corner almost three minutes
into injury time to spike the Gunners' hopes in a 1-1 draw.
</P>
<P>
Arsenal had earlier seemed to be coasting to victory after
Marc Overmars fired to put the Premiership champions ahead in the
51st minute.
</P>
<P>
Bayern Munich made a disastrous start to their Champions
League program here, going down 2-1 at Denmark's Brondby, who
came back with two late goals after going behind.
</P>
<P>
Bayern looked to have wrapped up an important smash-and-grab
win when Markus Babbel scored with a close-range header in the
77th minute following a Stefan Effenberg freekick.
</P>
<P>
But in a calamitous final three minutes for the Bavarians,
center back Thomas Helmer put through his own goal Helmer and
Allan Ravn netted a long-range winner seconds from time.
</P>
<P>
Olympiakos of Greece earned a 2-2 draw from Porto with two
goals in the final four minutes.
</P>
<P>
Zlatko Zahovic and Mario Jardel had given the Portuguese side
the lead before Stylianos Giannakopoulos, in the 86th minute and
then Sinica Gogic in the dying seconds brought Olympiakos a point.
</P>
<P>
French referee Gilles Veissiere was a busy man during the
night putting three players from each team into his notebook as
well as logging the four goals.
</P>
<P>
Real Madrid opened their title defence with a convincing 2-0
victory over 10-man Inter Milan.
</P>
<P>
Inter had defender Salvatore Fresi sent off just before
half-time but held out until the 80th minute, when Fernando
Hierro drove home a penalty. Dutchman Clarence Seedorf then
sealed victory in injury-time.
</P>
<P>
Real fully deserved their win after outclassing Inter in every
department, giving Ronaldo no chance to show his skills in the
Group C tie.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish side took charge right from the whistle, with not
only forwards Raul and Pimentel Savio but also overlapping
wingbacks Roberto Carlos and Christian Panucci all causing
trouble for the Inter defence.
</P>
<P>
A 65th-minute scorcher from Roar Strand secured a 1-1 draw for
Norwegian champions Rosenborg Trondheim at Athletic Bilbao at a
packed San Mames stadium here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Spanish international Joseba Etxeberria scored after just five
minutes for Bilbao following a mistake by Eric Hoftun but the
expected goalrush never materialised.
</P>
<P>
And Bundesliga champions Kaiserslautern had a Martin Wagner
goal to thank for a precious 1-0 win over Portugal's Benfica as
they launched their bid for glory in Group F. 
</P>
</TEXT>
