<HEADLINE> UK's Unemployment at Lowest since 1980 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Britain's unemployment has
continued to fall despite the recent spate of high profile
redundancy announcements.
</P>
<P>
Government figures show that in the three months to July the
main measure of unemployment dropped by 55,000 to 1,790,000, a
jobless rate of 6.2 percent. The older measure of unemployment,
which counts the number of people out of work and claiming
benefits, fell by 16,400 in August to 1.3 million, the lowest
level since May 1980.
</P>
<P>
The jobless figures were better than London's financial City
experts had predicted, with most forecasters expecting only a
modest fall, or even a rise, in unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Worries about the impact of the strong pound and fears of a new
recession in manufacturing left some analysts predicting that
unemployment had bottomed out and that dole queues were set to
rise again.
</P>
<P>
There have been a series of high-profile redundancy
announcements recently at Siemens and Fujitsu in the north east.
</P>
<P>
Britain's employment minister Andrew Smith welcomed the buoyant
labour statistics, saying that "The rate of employment in the UK
rose to 73.5 percent, the highest in Europe apart from Denmark,
and 8 percent higher than Germany and 13 percent higher than
France."
</P>
<P>
"Whilst these figures demonstrate government employment policy
success, there are some sectors of industry facing difficulties
and we are redoubling efforts to help people facing redundancy,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"Nevertheless, the overall picture is encouraging and the
government's drive for sustainable growth, investment in skills
and high employment in place of boom and bust, is on course," he
added.
</P>
<P>
"That is why it is important to view the recent job losses
reported in the media in the wider context of what is happening in
the labour market as a whole," he said.
</P>
<P>
Smith also welcomed the fall in average earnings figures,
noting that "The second successive fall in average earnings is
another factor in ensuring that we continue to have a healthy
labour market with low inflation.
</P>
<P>
"It is important, therefore, that employers continue to make
sure that increases in wages are in line with improvements in
productivity and what they can afford," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
