<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council to Boost Arms Embargo Scrutiny </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council on Wednesday unanimously adopted a resolution, calling
upon all member states to make efforts to outlaw the violations of
arms embargoes in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council "encourages each member state, as
appropriate, to consider the adoption of legislation or other
legal measures making the violation of arms embargoes established
by the Council a criminal offence," the resolution said.
</P>
<P>
The resolution requested the Security Council Committees
established by resolutions imposing arms embargoes in Africa to
include in their annual reports a substantive section on the
implementation of the arms embargoes, on possible violation of
measures reported to the Committee and with recommendation as
appropriate for strengthening the effective of the arms embargoes.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also urged member states, relevant United
Nations bodies and agencies and other international agencies to
consider the provision of technical and other assistance, in
consultation with the states concerned, to facilitate the
implementation of arms embargoes.
</P>
<P>
The resolution stressed that "arms embargoes established by
the Security Council should have clearly established objectives
and provisions for regular view of the measures with a view to
lifting them when the objectives are met."
</P>
<P>
The resolution came following the Security Council's formal
consideration of a report by Kofi Annan, the United Nations
secretary-general, which devoted details to the causes of
conflicts in Africa and the ways to ensure sustainable development
in the continent.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, together with a presidential statement on how
to strengthen peacekeeping capacity in Africa, coincided with
international and African efforts to bring an end to conflicts in
the Great Lakes region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
