<HEADLINE> Growth of World Economy Expected to drop 1.2 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Growth in the world
economy is expected to be 2 percent this year, a drop of 1.2
percentage points from 1997, according to U.N. Trade and
Development Report 1998 released here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This is due to the Asian economic crisis which is more serious
in terms of its scope and repercussions, than any other such
crisis in the past three decades, and its full effects have yet to
be felt, the U.N. Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD)
said in the report.
</P>
<P>
The cost of the crisis in East Asia is about 1 percent of
global output this year or some 260 billion U.S. dollars,
equivalent to the annual income of sub-Saharan Africa, it added.
</P>
<P>
For the first time in many years, growth in the developing
world will fall bellow that in the developed economies, to less
than 2.5 percent, half that of 1997, it said.
</P>
<P>
The Asian crisis will reduce both Gross Domestic Product and
export growth in the European Union by over 0.5 percentage points
this year while growth in Japan is expected to be negative for the
year.
</P>
<P>
In the United States, the excess of private spending over
incomes which has driven recent growth cannot continue, and "a
rougher landing than currently foreseen" is a distinct
possibility, the report continued.
</P>
<P>
Unless East Asia switches from deflation to reflation, and the
European countries and Japan boost global demand for goods and
services, there could be a full-blown global recession, the UNCTAD
warned.
</P>
<P>
The report said trade has been a key factor in spreading the
crisis and the growth of world trade in volume terms in 1998 will
drop well below the 1997 figure of 9.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The major industrial countries have to date gained more from
declining commodity prices and improving terms of trade than they
have lost from cuts in exports to Asia, UNCTAD argued. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
