<HEADLINE> Robertson: S-300 Missiles to Aggravate Tension in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Visiting British Defense
Secretary George Robertson said here Wednesday that the planned
deployment of the Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles in
Cyprus would aggravate the tension on the divided island republic.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after talks with his Greek counterpart, Akis
Tsohatzopoulos, Robertson said that the S-300 missiles did not add
anything to the security of Cyprus, but added to the existing
tension, and the priority now was to reduce tension there.
</P>
<P>
He would make one "differentiation" to the right of each
government to determine its defense program and asked whether it
was wise for the Cypriot government to purchase and deploy the
missiles.
</P>
<P>
But Tsohatzopoulos did not agree with Robertson's such views,
saying that Britain should look at the wider picture of reducing
armaments with the final aim of fully demilitarizing Cyprus, which
has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded and
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of a failed
coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Athens believed that a ban on military flights over Cyprus
could be the first step in reducing armaments, and this first step
could then be expanded to other areas, the minister stressed.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, which has rejected the proposal of imposing a military
flight ban over Cyprus, has threatened to use force to prevent the
installation of the missiles in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has insisted that it has the right to strengthen its
defense capacity to deal with Turkey's threat to its security.
</P>
<P>
Greece, which has a joint defense pact with Cyprus, has warned
that such strikes by Turkey would be a cause for war.
</P>
<P>
Robertson also described the Turkish side's proposal of
establishing a confederation of two states on Cyprus as
"impossible", saying that it ran counter to 25 years of United
Nations resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers also stressed the need of seeking a political
solution to the Kosovo problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
