<HEADLINE> Russian Ruble Dives by Nearly 23 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Russian ruble tumbled
again Wednesday, with the Central Bank's official rate shedding
22.8 percent amid fears of rising inflation.
</P>
<P>
The official rate, based on the average of trading on the
Moscow Interbank Currency Exchange (MICEX), fell to 12.45 to the
dollar from 9.6 to the dollar the day before.
</P>
<P>
Trading on MICEX, Russia's main trading floor, showed an even
steeper drop. The ruble fell to 12.59 rubles to the dollar at the
close of trade Wednesday, down from Tuesday's high of 7.3 rubles.
</P>
<P>
At exchange booths, dollars were being sold for over 15 rubles
to the dollar. But many banks ran out of dollars and closed down
exchange operations.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate on MICEX hit a low of 20.83 to the dollar a
week ago, but bounced back to 7.3 mid-Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the brief improvement in the ruble rate
before Tuesday was due to manipulation by Russian banks who owed
foreigners billions of dollars for forward contracts.
</P>
<P>
Some traders said that the Central Bank had also helped this
process by selling dollars and pushing up the ruble.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank has refused to comment on the allegations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
