<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., S.Korea Reach $2 Billion Export Credit Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Export-Import
Bank and South Korea reached an agreement on a two billion U.S.
dollars export credit program, allowing South Korean companies to
purchase U.S. goods and services.
</P>
<P>
"This important agreement represents Ex-Im Bank's critical role
in assisting U.S. exporters and should help to maintain trade
flows to (South) Korea, especiallys in response to the financial
situation in Asia," said Chairman James Harmon of the bank.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, the bank may make available as much as two
billion U.S. dollars to support exports of U.S. capital goods and
services to South Korea with repayment terms of up to five years.
</P>
<P>
The program is structured in two tranches, each for one billion
U.S. dollars, and financing extended will carry the sovereign
guarantee of the South Korean government.
</P>
<P>
The financing support in the program will be in the form of
direct loans to the Korean Development Bank, which will then use
loan to finance the purchase of U.S. capital goods and services.
</P>
<P>
The Ex-Im Bank is an independent U.S. government agency. In
fiscal year 1997, it supported 15 billion U.S. dollars of U.S.
exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
