<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Reiterates Stand on Cyprus' Missile Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkey reiterated Wednesday
that it will not allow the Russian-made S-300 missiles to be
deployed in Cyprus, according to the Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
To postpone the deployment of the missiles on the island is by
no means a substantial step to end the crisis created by Cyprus,
Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman Necati Utkan told a weekly
press conference.
</P>
<P>
"Arbitrary decisions for postponement will not bring a
solution to the present problems, will not change the essence
of the issue and will even cause the present situation to
deteriorate," Utkan said.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks while commenting on recent press
reports that the Cypriot government has decided to put off
deployment of the S-300 missiles till December. The deployment
was scheduled for November.
</P>
<P>
It is obvious that neither Turkey nor Turkish Cypriots can
tolerate the utilization of the S-300 missiles which is a constant
element of threat, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus signed a deal with Russia early last year to buy
the surface-to-air S-300 missiles to boost its defense capacity.
</P>
<P>
Annoyed by the act, Turkey has vowed to take all necessary
measures to deter the missiles from being deployed in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkish General Staff has urged Russia to give up
this arms contract with Cyprus. But this was turned down by
Moscow which said that Cyprus has the right to buy conventional
weapons.
</P>
<P>
Greece, a supporter of the Cypriot government, has also
said that it will stand firmly by the Greek Cypriots if they
are attacked by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish
troops intervened and took over the northern third of the
island in the wake of a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared the breakaway "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus" which is only recognized by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
At present, over 35,000-strong Turkish troops are stationed
in northern Cyprus to provide security protection to Turkish
Cypriots there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Police Uncover Child Abuse Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Four men pleaded guilty to the
sexual abuse of children Wednesday after British police cracked
a paedophile ring connected to a breakaway scouting group.
</P>
<P>
The trial of four men had led police to disclose their
discovery of a "huge network" of child abuse, police said.
</P>
<P>
Police said they were now trying to trace more than 50 boys who
may urgently need help.
</P>
<P>
The two scout groups involved -- both part of the UK Baden
Powell Scouting Association -- are nothing to do with the
mainstream Scout association.
</P>
<P>
One of the four men who pleaded at the Old Bailey was Brian
Turner, 60, a convicted paedophile who was a member of child
killer Sidney Cooke's "dirty dozen" gang.
</P>
<P>
Turner and three others -- Dennis Ward, 66, Keith Spratt, 50,
and Robert Kearns, 50 -- admitted sexually abusing the boy after
being introduced to him by a scoutmaster.
</P>
<P>
The boy was 10 years old when he joined one of the self-styled
scouting groups, which was run by scoutmaster Douglas Braithwaite,
who died last year.
</P>
<P>
Police have discovered thousands of pictures and videos hidden
in Kearns' home and are desperate to trace the children in the
pornographic images.
</P>
<P>
Some of these films were recovered abroad and showed some of
the men violently assaulting young children.
</P>
<P>
Five police forces are now involved in the inquiry, which has
spread to France, Belgium, the Netherlands and Spain, and could
involve as many as 300 victims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
