<HEADLINE> Ghana, Equatorial Guinea to Step up Coop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Ghana and Equatorial Guinea
have agreed to establish a joint committee for cooperation
between the two countries, as part of the moves to strengthen
bilateral economic ties.
</P>
<P>
Ghanaian President Jerry Rawlings and his Equatorial
counterpart, Teodoro Obiang Mbasogo expressed their commitment to
stronger ties in a joint communique issued in Accra Wednesday, at
the end of Mbasogo's three-day visit to Ghana.
</P>
<P>
According to a report from the Ghanaian capital, the two
leaders also expressed concern over external attempts to
destabilize Equatorial Guinea. However, it gave no further
details of the attempts.
</P>
<P>
The communique recounted the numerous conflicts on the
continent and called on the warring factions to abandon the use
of force in favor of peaceful negotiations.
</P>
<P>
It called on the feuding parties in Guinea Bissau to place the
interest of their people first and agree to negotiations for
durable peace.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders agreed on the need to improve and strengthen
bilateral relations in the fields such as petroleum exploration
and exploitation, agriculture, scientific and technical
cooperation, culture, tourism and security, the report said.
</P>
