<HEADLINE> UK Pledges to Honor Flight Ban on Yugoslav Carriers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The British government said
Wednesday that it would impose an immediate ban on all Yugoslav
carriers amid increasing verbal attacks from its European Union
(EU) partners.
</P>
<P>
Last week, EU countries agreed to impose an air ban on
Yugoslavia to punish Belgrade's alleged crackdown on ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo, but Britain originally said a 1959 bilateral
agreement with Belgrade meant it had to give a year's notice
before it could halt flights.
</P>
<P>
London's refusal to implement the EU flight ban has drawn angry
reactions from the other members of the 15-nation bloc and is
considered as an embarrassment for the EU foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
However, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said Wednesday
that Britain would change its position and ordered an immediate
ban on Yugoslav carriers in a bid to give the "continued
repressive activities" of Yugoslav troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"In the changed circumstances, we have concluded that it would
be right to proceed the immediate flight ban," Cook said. "The UK
is determined to strengthen the sanctions regime."
</P>
<P>
Cook also made it clear that Britain would press for "a U.N.
Security Council resolution, which would include a worldwide
flight ban on the FRY (Federal Republic of Yugoslavia)." 
</P>
</TEXT>
