<HEADLINE> Swazi King Calls for Peaceful Solution to Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 16 (Xinhua)-- The King of Swaziland
has called for an end to the civil strife in the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC), pointing out that peace can only be
achieved through dialog and negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Making the appeal on Tuesday night in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania,
visiting King Mswati III of Swaziland said that the continued war
in Congo (K) had an adverse effect on neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
"We share the belief that only dialog and negotiations can
bring an end to the crisis," Mswati said.
</P>
<P>
The 30-year-old monarch commended all those trying to find a
peaceful solution to the civil war of Congo which started on
August 2.
</P>
<P>
The Congolese Tutsi rebels and their allies have been trying
to forcefully remove from power President Laurent Kabila, who
toppled Mobutu Sese Seko in May of 1997.
</P>
<P>
King Mswati III, who is on a three-day state visit to Tanzania
together with h s wife, The Inkhosikati, pledged to work hand in
hand with all peace brokers in the region.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to work together to bring an end to the era
of instability in the Great Lakes region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa appealed warring
parties to come back to the negotiation table and decried that
the continued civil war in the DRC poses a soRP=UM"!IQ"=@Q!5RtK'.X6l peace and s
tability of the region.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania, in collaboration with the international community,
including the Organization of African Unity (OAU), is trying to
find a lasting solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
President Mkapa also pledged continued support for the Burundi
peace negotiations under the chairmanship of Julius Nyerere,
former president of Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by Tanzanian foreign minister Jakaya Kikwete and
Minister of Industries and Commerce Iddi Simba, King Mswati III
and his wife Wednesday visited the Tanzania-China Friendship
Textile Company Ltd. in Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
After touring the company, the royal couple and their
entourage left for Zanzibar where they were met at the airport by
the isles President Salmin Amour, who hosted them before they
flew to Kilimanjaro, north Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
King Mswati III is scheduled to return to Dar es Salaam
Thursday and end his visit later on that day. 
</P>
