<HEADLINE> Surviving Iranian Diplomat Appears on TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The only Iranian diplomat
who survived the massacre by the Afghan Taliban militia
appeared on Iran's state-run television Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
Allahdad Shahsavan Qare-Husseini, head of the secretariat of
the Iranian consulate in Mazari Sharif and in charge of the
refugee affairs, was shot and wounded in the massacre on August
8, but survived the killing.
</P>
<P>
Qare-Husseini said that around 1200 local times, a group of
seven or eight armed Taliban troops entered the Iranian consulate
in Mazari Sharif by force and confined all the 10 Iranians,
including nine diplomats and a correspondent of the official news
agency IRNA, in the consulate to a room.
</P>
<P>
One of the Taliban forces, apparently a Pakistani national,
asked for permission from the Iranians to make a call to Pakistan,
Qare-Husseini said, "we told him that he could use the telephone
to contact with Pakistan, however, he was prevented from making
the call by other Taliban members."
</P>
<P>
"Although we received them very well with water and fruits,
the Taliban forces transferred us to a small basement, putting us
behind a table," he said, then three Taliban soldiers opened fire
on the Iranians inside the basement.
</P>
<P>
Qare-Husseini said, "after one or two shots, I decided to lie
down on the ground to seek shelter under a table and fortunately
the table protected me from three sides, but my friends were
gunned down one by one."
</P>
<P>
"The consul general fell on my feet and was killed instantly,"
he said, "but I tried to control my breathing and closed my eyes
and waited to be martyred."
</P>
<P>
Qare-Husseini said that maybe the Taliban wanted to keep him
alive and left the basement.
</P>
<P>
"After the Taliban forces left the basement, I tried to stand
up, but found I was shot on the leg," the Iranian diplomat said,
however, the wound was not serious and he walked out of the
basement and found no one in the consulate.
</P>
<P>
Qare-Husseini said that he tried to make call twice to Iran but
failed.
</P>
<P>
At this moment, he found two of the Iranians were alive and
decided to go out to find help for the two injured Iranians, he
said, one of the consulate guards who hid inside the kitchen told
him to change his clothes to go out.
</P>
<P>
After disguising himself with Afghan clothes, Qare-Huseini
left the consulate and headed for the region controlled by
the Shiite group, however he was arrested by the Taliban with a
group of Afghans but later was released by a Taliban judge.
</P>
<P>
After fleeing from Mazari Sharif, Qare-Hussein said, he
traveled towards the Iranian border and succeeded to return to
Iran.
</P>
<P>
The bodies of six iranian diplomats and a correspondent of IRNA
were flown to Tehran Monday night, but the fate of another two
Iranian diplomats were not known. Iran believes that they are
still alive and are in the hands of the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
Iran has been massing troops along Iran-Afghan borders for
military manoeuvres, apparently getting ready for a show-down with
the Afghan Taliban regime which has seized almost 90 percent of
the country.
</P>
<P>
Iran has vowed to avenge the deaths of the diplomats while the
Taliban has denied direct involvement of the killing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
