<HEADLINE> Turkey Supports Iraq's Territorial Integrity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkey said Wednesday that
any arrangement to solve northern Iraq issue must be based on
the respect of territorial integrity of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a weekly press briefing here, Turkish Foreign
Ministry spokesman Necati Utkan called on all parties involved in
the negotiations should adopt a cautious attitude in dealing with
the issue.
</P>
<P>
"The whole problem is to fill the authority vacuum in northern
Iraq. An ultimate settlement should definitely be based on Iraq's
territorial integrity," Utkan said.
</P>
<P>
He referred to the ongoing talks in the United States between
Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) leader Massoud Barzani and his
rival Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) leader Jalal Talabani.
</P>
<P>
The forces of Barzani and Talabani have been engaged in fierce
fighting for the control of northern Iraq since the Saddam
Hussein government lost the effective control of the area
following the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The KDP has maintained a closer relationship with Ankara
due to its cooperation in fighting Turkey's outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party militants. The PUK, however, is allegedly backed
by Iran.
</P>
<P>
Utkan stressed that any new plan to be outlined should
not obstruct Turkey's struggle against the PKK which he said
uses northern Iraq as a base to launch terrorist attacks on
Turkey's military and civilian targets.
</P>
<P>
"What we highlight most regarding the efforts for hammering
out a compromise is our anticipation and hope that the new
order in question will make the struggle against the PKK more
efficient," he said.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that Barzani and Talabani will inform Ankara
about the outcome of their talks in Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
