<HEADLINE> Annan: UN to Facilitate Implementation of Anti-Landmine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
will facilitate the implementation of the anti-landmine
convention, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said here on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Annan made the remark after Burkina Faso this afternoon became
the 40th State to ratify the "Convention on the Prohibition of the
Use, Stockpiling, Production and Transfer of Anti-Personal Mines
and on Their Destruction", allowing its entry into force in six
months time.
</P>
<P>
"The entry into force of the Convention will have far-reaching
implications for both mine-affected and mine-producing countries.
It will provide the international legal framework upon which
governments who bind themselves to the Convention will be required
to take measures to break the chain of anti-personal landmine
use," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"As called for in the Convention, the United Nations will
facilitate its implementation. Also, through the UN Voluntary
Trust Fund for Assistance in Mine Clearance, the United Nations
will continue to play a key role in coordinating the response to
combat landmines," The U.N. chief said.
</P>
<P>
Annan expressed the hope that all of the world's nations will
promote universal adherence to the principles of the Convention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
