<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Rise But Off Highes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- European stock markets ended
the day on a positive note but off early highs as investors waited
to see how Wall Street would respond to U.S. Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan's testimony.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 ended cautiously higher Wednesday, closing
10.0 points up at 5,291.7 as traders waited anxiously for news of
U.S. interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Traders were waiting eagerly for a speech by Alan Greenspan,
U.S. Federal Reserve chairman, which could give a signal that U.S.
interest rates will be cut.
</P>
<P>
Shares in the French CAC 40 index grew 0.9 percent while
Spanish shares did better, rising 2.7 percent on the back of
extraordinary gains on Latin American markets.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones was 13 points ahead at 8,037 by the London close.
But UK data released Wednesday revealed a mixed picture on the
state of the economy.
</P>
<P>
A bigger than expected fall in average earnings was seen as
good news for inflation, but another fall in unemployment could
prompt the Bank of England to hold off cutting interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Traders took heart from comments made by Bank of England
governor Eddie George at the Trade Unions Congress conference,
where he promised to cut rates if inflation fell below government
target levels.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares closed slightly higher despite a
subdued early performance on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The Xetra Dax closed at 4,872.18, up 20.62 points from
Tuesday's close. The Dax closed floor trade up 26.75 at 4,857.97.
</P>
<P>
One trader said, "I feel much more confident today as I think
all the bad news has now been priced into shares. I think we will
now start to see the market making a steady climb back up,
reaching the 5,000 level by the end of the month."
</P>
<P>
In Paris, share prices closed higher but off their highs as
investors took profits towards the end of the session following
Wall Street's lukewarm opening.
</P>
<P>
The CAC 40 index finished 31.32 points higher at 3,729.32,
after rising as high as 3,771.78 in early afternoon.
</P>
<P>
One Paris trader said, "Like all European markets, we moved
with Wall Street. Some sector movements kept us higher, however,
like the banks coming up after being so low lately." 
</P>
</TEXT>
