<HEADLINE> Angola Wants to Maintain Current Coffee Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Angola will make a proposal
to maintain the current coffee prices in the international market
during a meeting of African Organization of Coffee in Britain, an
Angolan official said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Angolan secretary of state for coffee Gilberto Buta Lutucuta
said this before leaving for London to attend the meeting
scheduled on September 21-25.
</P>
<P>
Lutucuta said Angola hopes to maintain the current world
coffee prices, particularly of the Angolan-produced Robusta
coffee.
</P>
<P>
At present, one kilogram of the Robusta coffee fetches 1.60
U.S. Dollars in the international market while one kilogram of
the Arabian coffee is sold for 3.20 U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The price of any kind of product must be fixed properly," the
secretary of state noted. "To make profit from international
trade, they have to fetch practical and fair prices."
</P>
<P>
During the coming coffee conference, export quota will be
reset for each coffee producing country in order to maintain and
even raise the prices of coffee.
</P>
<P>
The secretary of state said coffee output in Angola is
expected to reach 10,000 tons, but due to many unpredictable
factors, Angola might gather in only 5,000 tons of coffee this
year.
</P>
<P>
Angola boasts of a century-long history of coffee growing. In
1974, its coffee output hit a record of 225,000 tons, ranking the
second in Africa and the fourth in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
