<HEADLINE> COMESA Members Urged to Pay Contributions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Members of the Common Market
for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) were urged Wednesday to
pay their contributions to the regional body's court of justice
so that iu could begin to function properly.
</P>
<P>
Opening the first session of the Lusaka-based COMESA court of
justice, Alfeyo Hambayi, acting minister of Commerce, Trade and
Industry, said out of the 20 member states only three have paid
their contributions to the court's budget, Zambia News Agency
ZANA reported.
</P>
<P>
Hambayi also urged the international community to extend its
assistance to the court of justice to ensure its smooth
operations.
</P>
<P>
"The court largely needs financial resources for capacity
building, equipment, furniture and transport," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hambayi further called on the judges of the court to maintain
independence on the bench and adjudicate fairly on matters before
them if the COMESA community is to have confidence in them.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the same occasion, COMESA acting secretary general
Sindiso Ngwenya said the court of justice will ensure the
adherence to the rule of law in the region.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the court of justice shall benefit the process
of economic integration as it would provide one integrated strong
judicial body with one registry.
</P>
<P>
"As COMESA moves toward the establishment of a free trade area
by the year 2000, there will be increasing demand for proper
interpretation of the COMESA trade regime," Ngwenya said.
</P>
<P>
The COMESA court of justice which comprises 11 judges was
established two months ago. It offers a means to redress unfairly
disadvantaged producers and traders in the region.
</P>
<P>
The progress to establish such a court was made at the COMESA
summit held in Lusaka last year. The court which has never been
operational siCOMESA came into being in 1994 will arbitrate
and preside on cases involving unfair trade practices,
interpretation of the COMESA treaty provisions and ensure that
member states implement and comply with agreed decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polls: Public Opinion Favors Censuring Clinton  Rather than Impeachment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Public opinion after the
release of Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's report remains in
favor of censuring President Bill Clinton rather than impeaching
him or seeking his resignation.
</P>
<P>
A CBS News-New York Times poll released Tuesday and a CNN/USA
Today/Gallup poll released Wednesday show Clinton maintaining a
robust job approval rating above 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
A majority of Americans still oppose ousting Clinton from
office, with the CBS-Times poll finding 58 percent against
beginning impeachment hearings over his affair with a White House
intern and effort to cover it up, and 64 percent saying they do
not think Clinton should resign. But 57 percent believe Congress
should censure Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The CNN-USA Today poll found 45 percent favoring a reprimand or
censure, but allowing Clinton to remain in office. However, 50
percent favored congressional hearings to investigate the charges
in the report and, among likely voters, 58 percent favored
hearings.
</P>
<P>
The public remains critical of Clinton's personal behavior.
Sixty-six percent of those polled in the CBS-Times survey said
Clinton does not share the moral values that most Americans try to
live by, and 45 percent have an unfavorable opinion of him.
</P>
<P>
And the CNN-USA Today survey found a statistical dead heat over
who people preferred to have more influence over the direction the
nation takes in the next year: 44 percent Clinton and 43 percent
the Republicans in Congress. Among likely voters, 50 percent
wanted the Republican to have more influence and 38 percent
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The same survey of likely voters found 48 percent are likely
for vote Democratic in the upcoming congressional elections and 47
percent Republican.
</P>
<P>
The CBS-Times telephone poll of 1,813 adults conducted between
September 12-14 had a margin of error of plus or minus 3
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
The CNN-USA Today survey of 1,028 adults September 14-15 had a
margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage points. The subgroup
of 401 likely voters had a margin of error of plus or minus 5
percentage points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
