<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Double Trade Experts in Africa: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States
plans to double its trade specialists in Africa and triple the
number of countries with commerce offices in the continent by the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The strategic plan was unveiled by U.S. Secretary of Commerce
William Daley, who arrived here Wednesday for a brief visit to
bring a positive commercial message against the backdrop of the
tragic bombings last month.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference at the Sheraton Hotel in Dar es
Salaam, Daley said the plan includes opening a Foreign Commerce
Service in Dar es Salaam to be staffed with one American and two
Tanzanians.
</P>
<P>
"I will fight to make that happen," said Daley, who has been
the third senior government official who visited Tanzania since
the bombing of the U.S. embassy, following Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and the Director of the Federal Bureau of
Ilvestigation (FBI) Louis Freech who came here last month.
</P>
<P>
"We are developing an African Commercial Strategy at the
Commerce Department," he said, adding that he wishes every agency
under his leadership to tighten ties with Africa and all people
in the society to lend support.
</P>
<P>
Daley said: "I want every agency at Commerce to ask: how can
we strengthen our partnership with Africa? I want our weather
forecasters, our patent lawyers, our telecommunication experts,
our scientists, our economists to help."
</P>
<P>
The United States is ready to be a full partner in Tanzania's
-- and this region's -- economic development. Last year, two-way
trade reached 92 million U.S. Dollars, compared with 65 million
in 1996, he said.
</P>
<P>
Daley said this year he will spend more time in Africa than
Latin America, Europe, Asia or any other part of the world. "This
is very different from past years," he added.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the twin bombings of U.S. embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania on August 7, he said, the Commerce Department lost two
employees -- both Kenyans. Four others were injured, two very
seriously. Altogether it has 48 employees in Africa stationed in
five countries.
</P>
<P>
He said the terrorist attacks, which killed more than 260
people and injured 5,000 others, have interrupted his planned
trade mission to Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said he has come to Dar es Salaam to see the situation
first-hand, and convey the message that the Clinton
administration is committed to help "rebuild both lives and
property."
</P>
<P>
Daley disclosed that the U.S. Congress is studying a proposal
for aid to help Tanzanians rebuild after the August 7 bombing of
the U.S. embassy in Dar Es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
Before flying to Nairobi, Kenya Wednesday afternoon, Daley had
held talks with Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa and Iddi
Simba, the Minister of Industries and Commerce, and toured the
bombed embassy site where he laid a wreath.
</P>
<P>
Daley had earlier visited South Africa, where a bomb blast
ripped through U.S.-franchise Planet Hollywood restaurant on
August 26.
" He will return to Africa in December for a five-nation tour
accompanied by a large group of U.S. business leaders seeking to
promote links and investments in the chemical, car,
telecommunications and energy sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
