<HEADLINE> U.S. Commerce Secretary in Kenya to Promote Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Commerce Secretary
William Daley arrived Wednesday evening in Nairobi, the third and
final stop of his four-day African tour aiming at strengthening
U.S.-African trade ties.
</P>
<P>
Daley will hold talks Thursday with Kenyan President Daniml
arap Moi, Trade Minister Joseph Kamotho and other senior Kenyan
officials and prominent U.S. and Kenyan businessmen.
</P>
<P>
"Strengthening commercial ties between Kenya and the U.S. was
the original purpose for planning a trip to Kenya," he said in an
arrival statement.
</P>
<P>
"While I am in Kenya, I also look forward to meeting with
leaders from regional organizations from east Africa. Together we
can build the valuable partnerships between our public and
private sectors that can contribute to economic growth, export
expansion, and job creation," he said.
</P>
<P>
He was scheduled to make speeches respectively Thursday to the
American Business Association and the 23rd annual conference of
the International Organization of Securities Commissions (IOSCO)
which opened Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He will also pay a tribute to the bombing site in downtown
Nairobi where 253 people, including 12 Americans, were killed on
August 7 by a car bomb aimed at the U.S. embassy in downtown
Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, Daley said in Dar es Salaam, the capital of
Tanzania that the increasing U.S. investment in Tanzania is
playing an active role in helpifg trigger much-needed economic
growth for the country.
</P>
<P>
He also called for the removal of regional trade barriers
which are a major obstacle to growth.
</P>
<P>
Daley started his second African trip this year in South
africa, the continent's economic giant, on Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He will return to Africa -- and to Nairobi -- in December for
a five-nation tour accompanied by a large group of U.S. business
leaders seeking to promote trade and investments in the chemical,
automobile, telecommunications and energy sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
