<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earth Citizens Urged to Buy Ozone-Friendly Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Every citizen on earth
can help preserve ozone layer by buying only ozone-friendly
products, said U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In his message on the occasion of the International Day for the
Preservation of the Ozone Layer, Annan said this year's theme is
"For life on earth: Buy ozone-friendly."
</P>
<P>
"Such choices can not only prod industries to switch to
ozone-friendly technologies, but can also help reduce illegal
trade and ensure that countries fulfill their obligations under
the Montreal Protocol," he said.
</P>
<P>
Despite a reduction of over 80 percent in the production and
consumption of ozone-depleting chemicals in the last 10 years, the
risk to tomorrow's health and well-being remains acute as mankind
faces many challenges, he said.
</P>
<P>
The recovery of the ozone layer will begin in a few years and
will take up to the year 2060 to complete due to the long lifetime
of the chemicals in the atmosphere, Annan said, calling the
depletion of ozone layer "the first major global environmental
issue to be tackled by the U.N. system."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. system first took the issue of ozone depletion in
1976 and the 1987 Montreal Protocol set up phase-out schedules
for different countries according to their development levels.
</P>
<P>
Due to the fact that developed nations are responsible for the
bulk of total emissions into the atmosphere, developing countries
have been given a grace period of 10 years and will begin their
phase-out in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0339 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 85 Percent Zambian Children in School: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Education Minister
Godfrey Miyanda said Wednesday that only 85 percent Zambian
school-age children are accepted in schools, according to Zambia
News Agency ZANA.
</P>
<P>
While opening an appraisal mission here on the Basic Education
Sub-sector Investment Program (BESSIP), Miyanda said a
significant number of those Zambian children who enroll in grade
one are unable to go to higher grades especially in grades four
and five while 37 percent of the grade seven le};2rs are unable
to progress further.
</P>
<P>
Miyanda pointed out that out of the country's population of
9.5 million people, 1.5 million were school-age children between
seven and 13 years and of this number over 650,000 including
250,000 orphans are not in school.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the number of orphans in Zambia will reach
600,000 by the year 2000 with the associated problems of an
increasing number of child-headed households brought about by the
problem of HIV/AIDS pandemic.
</P>
<P>
The education minister also noted that quality of education
has been affected by a lack of adequate teaching and learning
materials at all levels of education while at primary level the
system is characterized by double and triple sessions leading to
short learning time.
</P>
<P>
According to Miyanda, the Education Ministry has received
between 1990 and 1996 an average of 13 percent of the total
budget allocation which is far below the regional average of 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
He said a chronic underfunding of the education sector due to
the country's overall poor economic decline is a main factor that
hinders the development of education. Enditfm

NNNN
05:09 05:09 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
