<DOCNO> XIE19980917.0340 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho Opposition May Reject Poll Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho's opposition
parties have threatened to reject the report on fraud allegations
in Lesotho's general election, which South Afric!$said would be
released Thursday, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Frank Chikane, secretary-general of South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki's office, told reporters Wednesday that the
report would be finally handed over to the Lesotho people
Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki failed to release the report last Wednesday. Instead, he
withheld it so that the presidents of the troika guarantors of
Lesotho's democracy -- South Africa, Botswana and Zimbabwe --
could view the contents first.
</P>
<P>
There are signs that Lesotho opposition parties may reject the
report.
</P>
<P>
Bosotholand Congress Party leader Malapo Qhobela told South
Africa's SABC television that he was on the verge of telling the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) leaders who delayed
the report's release that it was no longer needed.
</P>
<P>
"Very soon we shall take a decision that these people, who are
running up and down with the property of this nation (the
report), can keep it... we no longer need it. Very soon we shall
say so," he said.
</P>
<P>
Qhobela accused the SADC leaders of sidelining the report to
plan military action against Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
Chikane explained that the delay in releasing the report had
been caused by the logistical problems of getting the leaders of
the troika countries in the same place at the same time. There
was nothing sinister in the delay. The report was intact and it
had not been tampered with.
</P>
<P>
He accused protesters of using the delay as an excuse for
further agitation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
